{"title_page": "Port of Beirut", "text_new": "{{Infobox Port\n| name =Port of Beirut<br>\u0645\u0631\u0641\u0623 \u0628\u064a\u0631\u0648\u062a\n| image =\n| imagesize =275px\n| caption =\n| country =[[Lebanon]]\n| location =[[Beirut]]\n| coordinates ={{coord|33|54|10.62|N|35|31|4.04|E|type:landmark_region:LB|display=inline,title}}\n| opened =1887\n| operated =Gestion et exploitation du port de Beyrouth (GEPB)\n| owner =[[Government of Lebanon]]\n| type =Artificial\n| sizewater =1.002 km<sup>2</sup>\n| sizeland = \n| size =1.2 km<sup>2</sup>\n| berths =16\n| wharfs =\n| piers =\n| employees =639\n| leadershiptitle =General Manager\n| leader =Hassan Koraytem\n| blankdetailstitle1 =\n| blankdetails1 =\n| blankdetailstitle2 =\n| blankdetails2 =\n| blankdetailstitle3 =\n| blankdetails3 =\n| arrivals = 2,395 (2009)\n| cargotonnage = 5.8 million [[tonne]]s (2009)\n| containervolume = 994,601 [[Twenty-foot equivalent unit|TEU]] (2009)\n| cargovalue =\n| passengertraffic =6,699 (2009)\n| revenue =$163,486,146 (2009)\n| profit =\n| blankstatstitle1 =\n| blankstats1 =\n| blankstatstitle2 =\n| blankstats2 =\n| blankstatstitle3 =\n| blankstats3 =\n| website =[http://www.portofbeirut.com www.portofbeirut.com]\n}}\nThe '''Port of Beirut''' ({{lang-ar|\u0645\u0631\u0641\u0623 \u0628\u064a\u0631\u0648\u062a}}) is the main port in [[Lebanon]] located on the eastern part of the [[Saint George Bay]] on Beirut's northern Mediterranean coast, west of the [[Beirut River]].  It is one of the largest and busiest ports on the Eastern [[Mediterranean]].<ref>[http://www.lebanonembassyus.org/country_lebanon/economy.html The Economy  (Major Sectors of the Economy)] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130908003830/http://www.lebanonembassyus.org/country_lebanon/economy.html |date=2013-09-08 }}, Lebanese Embassy of the U.S.</ref> The Port of Beirut and [[Beirut Rafic Hariri International Airport]] are the main ports of entry into the country.\n==Data==\n\nThe port is operated and managed by the Gestion et exploitation du port de Beyrouth (GEPB),<ref>[http://www.portdebeyrouth.com/history.asp?x=2 History] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071214053106/http://www.portdebeyrouth.com/history.asp?x=2 |date=2007-12-14 }}, Port of Beirut</ref> which is [[French language|French]] for Port Authority of Beirut. Container terminal operations are subcontracted to a private consortium called the Beirut Container Terminal Consortium (BCTC).\n\nSince the end of the [[Lebanese Civil War]] in 1990, the port has gone through a major updating and expansion program with the rehabilitation of existing port facilities, the construction of new administration buildings, and the construction of a new container terminal.\n\nIt's an important gateway for transporting freight to [[Syria]], [[Jordan]], [[Iraq]], and the [[Persian Gulf States]].\n\nThe Port of Beirut has a total area of 1,200,000m<sup>2</sup> and has 4 [[dock (maritime)|basins]], 16 [[quays]], and a new [[container terminal]] at quay 16 capable of handling {{TEU|745,000|first=yes}} per year.\n\nThe [[free port|Free Zone]] includes three industrial buildings with warehouses covering a total area of 32,400m<sup>2</sup> and a commercial building with 46 [[duty-free]] shops covering an area of 11,200m<sup>2</sup>. In 2007, the Logistic Free Zone (LFZ) was established containing several logistics warehouses where goods can undergo transformations before being exported via land, sea, and air or imported into Lebanon.\n\nThe general cargo area consists of 12 warehouses and a [[storage silo|grain silo]] with a capacity of 120,000 tons of grain.\n\nThe Port of Beirut has been selected as a [[transshipment|transshipment hub]] for the second and third largest container shipping companies in the world, Swiss-based [[Mediterranean Shipping Company]] (MSC) and French-based [[CMA CGM|Compagnie Maritime d\u2019Affr\u00e8tement - Compagnie G\u00e9n\u00e9rale Maritime]] (CMA-CGM). The latter building a $12 million regional headquarters building near the port.\n\nThe passenger terminal is located along quay 5 facing the second basin of the port. The facility was deemed outdated and inadequate, so it is being reconstructed into a modern 600m<sup>2</sup> facility that will have a decorative front sail structure. It is scheduled for completion early this year.\n\nThe historic first basin of the port, which hosts the [[Beirut Naval Base]], will be completely redeveloped by [[Solidere]], the $2 billion Lebanese real estate company that is rebuilding the [[Beirut Central District]] (BCD). The redevelopment will involve transforming quays 1 and 2 into a public promenade along with the construction of leisure commercial properties.\n\nThe port lacks a railway connection, however, as part of long term plans to reinstate the [[OCFTC|railway system in Lebanon]], plans are to have a railway link to the port.\n[[File:Hafen von Beirut.jpg|thumb|Old docks in the [[Beirut]] Port]]\n\n==Beirut Container Terminal Consortium==\nManagement and operation of the container terminal is subcontracted to the Beirut Container Terminal Consortium (BCTC) which is made up of the Lebanese-based International Port Management Beirut (IPMB),  British-based Portia Management Services (PMS), and American-based Logistics and Port Management, Americas (LPMA). It was established in December 2004 and began operations in 2005, although the container terminal facilities were completed in 2000.\n\nThe majority of container traffic is handled by the new quay 16, the longest and deepest of all the quays at a length of 600m and a [[draft (hull)|draft]] of 15.5m allowing it to accommodate the largest [[container ships]] in the world. It has a stacking area of 365,000m<sup>2</sup> allowing it to process up to 745,000 [[Twenty-foot equivalent unit|TEU]] per year.\n\nQuay 16 is equipped with 6 [[Super-post-Panamax]] [[container crane]]s and 18 [[rubber tyred gantry crane]]s manufactured by [[Zhenhua|Shanghai Zhenhua Heavy Industry Company]] (ZPMC). \n\nDue to the very high traffic the container terminal is experiencing, the BCTC reached an agreement with the port authority to utilize the older quays 12, 13, and 14 for handling smaller container ships when quay 16 is occupied. This allows the container terminal to process up to 1,200,000 TEU per year and reduce vessel wait times. Container ships that are processed at these older quays as well as quay 15 have their containers loaded and unloaded by two [[mobile crane|mobile harbour cranes]] manufactured by [[Gottwald Port Technology]].\n\n===Expansion===\n====Phase I====\nThe first phase of the container terminal expansion was launched last year and involves expanding quay 16 by 500m to the east reaching the mouth of the [[Beirut River]] by reclaiming 140,000m<sup>2</sup> of land creating a new 180,000m<sup>2</sup> stacking area for containers. This will extend the quay from its present 600m to 1,100m. The [[draft (hull)|draft]] along the expanded quay will be 17.5m. The existing detached [[breakwater (structure)|breakwater]] for quay 16 will also be extended. The expansion will increase the container terminal capacity by 450,000 TEU allowing the terminal to process 1,500,000 TEU per year. The Danish-Lebanese joint venture, Pihl-Hourie, won the contract for the expansion project which will cost $128 million and be completed in 2012.\n====Phase II====\nOnce the first phase is completed in 2012, the second phase will be launched which will involve filling in the 4th basin of the port, bridging quays 12 and 16, creating a continuous 2,300m long quay increasing the container terminal capacity by 600,000 TEU allowing the terminal to process 2,100,000 TEU per year.\n\n==Pollution from ships==\nSee [[Marine environmental issues in Lebanon]]\n\n==Endnotes==\n===References===\n<references/>\n==External links==\n* [http://www.portofbeirut.com/ Port of Beirut]\n* [http://www.bctc-lb.com/ Beirut Container Terminal Consortium]\n\n[[Category:Beirut]]\n[[Category:Economy of Lebanon]]\n[[Category:Transport in Lebanon]]\n[[Category:Ports and harbors of Lebanon]]\n[[Category:Ports and harbours of the Arab League]]\n[[Category:Transport in the Arab League]]\n[[Category:Free ports|Beirut]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox Port\n| name =Port of Beirut<br>\u0645\u0631\u0641\u0623 \u0628\u064a\u0631\u0648\u062a\n| image =\n| imagesize =275px\n| caption =\n| country =[[Lebanon]]\n| location =[[Beirut]]\n| coordinates ={{coord|33|54|10.62|N|35|31|4.04|E|type:landmark_region:LB|display=inline,title}}\n| opened =1887\n| operated =Gestion et exploitation du port de Beyrouth (GEPB)\n| owner =[[Government of Lebanon]]\n| type =Artificial\n| sizewater =1.002 km<sup>2</sup>\n| sizeland = \n| size =1.2 km<sup>2</sup>\n| berths =16\n| wharfs =\n| piers =\n| employees =639\n| leadershiptitle =General Manager\n| leader =Hassan Koratiem\n| blankdetailstitle1 =\n| blankdetails1 =\n| blankdetailstitle2 =\n| blankdetails2 =\n| blankdetailstitle3 =\n| blankdetails3 =\n| arrivals = 2,395 (2009)\n| cargotonnage = 5.8 million [[tonne]]s (2009)\n| containervolume = 994,601 [[Twenty-foot equivalent unit|TEU]] (2009)\n| cargovalue =\n| passengertraffic =6,699 (2009)\n| revenue =$163,486,146 (2009)\n| profit =\n| blankstatstitle1 =\n| blankstats1 =\n| blankstatstitle2 =\n| blankstats2 =\n| blankstatstitle3 =\n| blankstats3 =\n| website =[http://www.portofbeirut.com www.portofbeirut.com]\n}}\nThe '''Port of Beirut''' ({{lang-ar|\u0645\u0631\u0641\u0623 \u0628\u064a\u0631\u0648\u062a}}) is the main port in [[Lebanon]] located on the eastern part of the [[Saint George Bay]] on Beirut's northern Mediterranean coast, west of the [[Beirut River]].  It is one of the largest and busiest ports on the Eastern [[Mediterranean]].<ref>[http://www.lebanonembassyus.org/country_lebanon/economy.html The Economy  (Major Sectors of the Economy)] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130908003830/http://www.lebanonembassyus.org/country_lebanon/economy.html |date=2013-09-08 }}, Lebanese Embassy of the U.S.</ref> The Port of Beirut and [[Beirut Rafic Hariri International Airport]] are the main ports of entry into the country.\n==Data==\n\nThe port is operated and managed by the Gestion et exploitation du port de Beyrouth (GEPB),<ref>[http://www.portdebeyrouth.com/history.asp?x=2 History] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071214053106/http://www.portdebeyrouth.com/history.asp?x=2 |date=2007-12-14 }}, Port of Beirut</ref> which is [[French language|French]] for Port Authority of Beirut. Container terminal operations are subcontracted to a private consortium called the Beirut Container Terminal Consortium (BCTC).\n\nSince the end of the [[Lebanese Civil War]] in 1990, the port has gone through a major updating and expansion program with the rehabilitation of existing port facilities, the construction of new administration buildings, and the construction of a new container terminal.\n\nIt's an important gateway for transporting freight to [[Syria]], [[Jordan]], [[Iraq]], and the [[Persian Gulf States]].\n\nThe Port of Beirut has a total area of 1,200,000m<sup>2</sup> and has 4 [[dock (maritime)|basins]], 16 [[quays]], and a new [[container terminal]] at quay 16 capable of handling {{TEU|745,000|first=yes}} per year.\n\nThe [[free port|Free Zone]] includes three industrial buildings with warehouses covering a total area of 32,400m<sup>2</sup> and a commercial building with 46 [[duty-free]] shops covering an area of 11,200m<sup>2</sup>. In 2007, the Logistic Free Zone (LFZ) was established containing several logistics warehouses where goods can undergo transformations before being exported via land, sea, and air or imported into Lebanon.\n\nThe general cargo area consists of 12 warehouses and a [[storage silo|grain silo]] with a capacity of 120,000 tons of grain.\n\nThe Port of Beirut has been selected as a [[transshipment|transshipment hub]] for the second and third largest container shipping companies in the world, Swiss-based [[Mediterranean Shipping Company]] (MSC) and French-based [[CMA CGM|Compagnie Maritime d\u2019Affr\u00e8tement - Compagnie G\u00e9n\u00e9rale Maritime]] (CMA-CGM). The latter building a $12 million regional headquarters building near the port.\n\nThe passenger terminal is located along quay 5 facing the second basin of the port. The facility was deemed outdated and inadequate, so it is being reconstructed into a modern 600m<sup>2</sup> facility that will have a decorative front sail structure. It is scheduled for completion early this year.\n\nThe historic first basin of the port, which hosts the [[Beirut Naval Base]], will be completely redeveloped by [[Solidere]], the $2 billion Lebanese real estate company that is rebuilding the [[Beirut Central District]] (BCD). The redevelopment will involve transforming quays 1 and 2 into a public promenade along with the construction of leisure commercial properties.\n\nThe port lacks a railway connection, however, as part of long term plans to reinstate the [[OCFTC|railway system in Lebanon]], plans are to have a railway link to the port.\n[[File:Hafen von Beirut.jpg|thumb|Old docks in the [[Beirut]] Port]]\n\n==Beirut Container Terminal Consortium==\nManagement and operation of the container terminal is subcontracted to the Beirut Container Terminal Consortium (BCTC) which is made up of the Lebanese-based International Port Management Beirut (IPMB),  British-based Portia Management Services (PMS), and American-based Logistics and Port Management, Americas (LPMA). It was established in December 2004 and began operations in 2005, although the container terminal facilities were completed in 2000.\n\nThe majority of container traffic is handled by the new quay 16, the longest and deepest of all the quays at a length of 600m and a [[draft (hull)|draft]] of 15.5m allowing it to accommodate the largest [[container ships]] in the world. It has a stacking area of 365,000m<sup>2</sup> allowing it to process up to 745,000 [[Twenty-foot equivalent unit|TEU]] per year.\n\nQuay 16 is equipped with 6 [[Super-post-Panamax]] [[container crane]]s and 18 [[rubber tyred gantry crane]]s manufactured by [[Zhenhua|Shanghai Zhenhua Heavy Industry Company]] (ZPMC). \n\nDue to the very high traffic the container terminal is experiencing, the BCTC reached an agreement with the port authority to utilize the older quays 12, 13, and 14 for handling smaller container ships when quay 16 is occupied. This allows the container terminal to process up to 1,200,000 TEU per year and reduce vessel wait times. Container ships that are processed at these older quays as well as quay 15 have their containers loaded and unloaded by two [[mobile crane|mobile harbour cranes]] manufactured by [[Gottwald Port Technology]].\n\n===Expansion===\n====Phase I====\nThe first phase of the container terminal expansion was launched last year and involves expanding quay 16 by 500m to the east reaching the mouth of the [[Beirut River]] by reclaiming 140,000m<sup>2</sup> of land creating a new 180,000m<sup>2</sup> stacking area for containers. This will extend the quay from its present 600m to 1,100m. The [[draft (hull)|draft]] along the expanded quay will be 17.5m. The existing detached [[breakwater (structure)|breakwater]] for quay 16 will also be extended. The expansion will increase the container terminal capacity by 450,000 TEU allowing the terminal to process 1,500,000 TEU per year. The Danish-Lebanese joint venture, Pihl-Hourie, won the contract for the expansion project which will cost $128 million and be completed in 2012.\n====Phase II====\nOnce the first phase is completed in 2012, the second phase will be launched which will involve filling in the 4th basin of the port, bridging quays 12 and 16, creating a continuous 2,300m long quay increasing the container terminal capacity by 600,000 TEU allowing the terminal to process 2,100,000 TEU per year.\n\n==Pollution from ships==\nSee [[Marine environmental issues in Lebanon]]\n\n==Endnotes==\n===References===\n<references/>\n==External links==\n* [http://www.portofbeirut.com/ Port of Beirut]\n* [http://www.bctc-lb.com/ Beirut Container Terminal Consortium]\n\n[[Category:Beirut]]\n[[Category:Economy of Lebanon]]\n[[Category:Transport in Lebanon]]\n[[Category:Ports and harbors of Lebanon]]\n[[Category:Ports and harbours of the Arab League]]\n[[Category:Transport in the Arab League]]\n[[Category:Free ports|Beirut]]\n", "name_user": "Haythamdouaihy", "label": "safe", "comment": "typo", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Port_of_Beirut"}
{"title_page": "Hydrodynamic escape", "text_new": "'''Hydrodynamic escape''' refers to a thermal [[atmospheric escape]] mechanism that can lead to the escape of heavier atoms of a [[planet]]ary [[Celestial body atmosphere|atmosphere]] through numerous collisions with lighter atoms.\n[[File:Hydrodynamic_escape.png|thumb|Schematic of hydrodynamic escape. Energy from solar radiation is deposited in a thin shell. This energy heats the atmosphere, which then begins to expand. This expansion continues into the vacuum of space, accelerating as it goes until it escapes.]]\n\n== Description ==\nHydrodynamic escape occurs if there is a strong thermally driven atmospheric escape of light atoms which, through drag effects (collisions), also drive off heavier atoms.<ref>{{cite book |title= Giant planets of our solar system: an introduction |last= Irwin|first=Patrick G. J. |authorlink= |date= 2006|publisher= Birkh\u00e4user |location= |isbn=3-540-31317-6 |page=58 |url= https://books.google.com/books?id=D6HZKSKg6P0C|accessdate= 22 Dec 2009}}</ref> The heaviest species of atom that can be removed in this manner is called the ''cross-over'' mass.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Hunten|first=Donald M.|last2=Pepin|first2=Robert O.|last3=Walker|first3=James C. G.|date=1987-03-01|title=Mass fractionation in hydrodynamic escape|journal=Icarus|volume=69|issue=3|pages=532\u2013549|doi=10.1016/0019-1035(87)90022-4|issn=0019-1035|hdl=2027.42/26796}}</ref>\n\nIn order to maintain a significant hydrodynamic escape, a large source of energy at a certain altitude is required.  [[Soft X-ray]] or [[extreme ultraviolet]] radiation, momentum transfer from impacting [[meteoroid]]s or [[asteroid]]s, or the heat input from planetary [[Accretion (astrophysics)|accretion processes]]<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=RaJdy3_VINQC|title=Planetary sciences|last=Pater|first=Imke De|author2=Jack Jonathan Lissauer|date=2001|publisher=[[Cambridge University Press]]|isbn=0-521-48219-4|location=|page=129|authorlink=|accessdate=}}</ref> may provide the requisite energy for hydrodynamic escape.\n\n== Calculations ==\nEstimating the rate of hydrodynamic escape is important in analyzing both the history and current state of a planet's atmosphere. In 1981, Watson et al. published<ref name=\":12\">{{Cite journal|last=Watson|first=Andrew J.|last2=Donahue|first2=Thomas M.|last3=Walker|first3=James C.G.|date=November 1981|title=The dynamics of a rapidly escaping atmosphere: Applications to the evolution of Earth and Venus|journal=Icarus|volume=48|issue=2|pages=150\u2013166|doi=10.1016/0019-1035(81)90101-9|hdl=2027.42/24204|url=https://deepblue.lib.umich.edu/bitstream/2027.42/24204/1/0000463.pdf}}</ref> calculations that describe energy-limited escape, where all incoming energy is balanced by escape to space. Recent numerical simulations on exoplanets have suggested that this calculation overestimates the hydrodynamic flux by 20 - 100 times.<sup>[30]</sup> However, as an special case and upper limit approximation on the atmospheric escape, it is worth noting here.\n\nHydrodynamic escape [[flux]] (<math>\\Phi</math>, [m<math>^{-2}</math>s<math>^{-1}</math>]) in an energy-limited escape can calculated, assuming (1) an atmosphere composed of non-[[Viscosity|viscous]], (2) constant molecular weight gas, with (3) [[Isotropy|isotropic]] pressure, (4) fixed temperature, (5) perfect XUV absorption, and that (6) pressure decreases to zero as distance from the planet increases.<ref name=\":12\"/>\n\n<math>\\Phi=\\frac{F_{XUV} R_p R_{XUV}^2}{G M_p}</math>\n\nwhere <math>F_{XUV}</math> is the [[photon]] flux [J m<math>^{-2}</math>s<math>^{-1}</math>] over the wavelengths of interest, <math>R_p</math> is the radius of the planet, <math>G</math>is the [[gravitational constant]], <math>M_p</math> is the mass of the planet, and <math>R_{XUV}</math> is the effective radius where the XUV absorption occurs. Corrections to this model have been proposed over the years to account for the [[Roche lobe]] of a planet and efficiency in absorbing photon flux.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Erkaev|first=N. V.|last2=Kulikov|first2=Yu. N.|last3=Lammer|first3=H.|last4=Selsis|first4=F.|last5=Langmayr|first5=D.|last6=Jaritz|first6=G. F.|last7=Biernat|first7=H. K.|date=September 2007|title=Roche lobe effects on the atmospheric loss from \"Hot Jupiters\"|journal=Astronomy & Astrophysics|volume=472|issue=1|pages=329\u2013334|doi=10.1051/0004-6361:20066929|issn=0004-6361}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Lecavelier des Etangs|first=A.|date=January 2007|title=A diagram to determine the evaporation status of extrasolar planets|journal=Astronomy & Astrophysics|volume=461|issue=3|pages=1185\u20131193|doi=10.1051/0004-6361:20065014|issn=0004-6361|arxiv=astro-ph/0609744}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Tian|first=Feng|last2=G\u00fcdel|first2=Manuel|last3=Johnstone|first3=Colin P.|last4=Lammer|first4=Helmut|last5=Luger|first5=Rodrigo|last6=Odert|first6=Petra|date=April 2018|title=Water Loss from Young Planets|journal=Space Science Reviews|volume=214|issue=3|doi=10.1007/s11214-018-0490-9|issn=0038-6308}}</ref>\n\nHowever, as computational power has improved, increasingly sophisticated models have emerged, incorporating [[radiative transfer]], [[photochemistry]], and [[hydrodynamics]] that provide better estimates of hydrodynamic escape.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Owen|first=James E.|date=2019-05-30|title=Atmospheric Escape and the Evolution of Close-In Exoplanets|journal=Annual Review of Earth and Planetary Sciences|volume=47|issue=1|pages=67\u201390|doi=10.1146/annurev-earth-053018-060246|issn=0084-6597|arxiv=1807.07609}}</ref>\n\n== Isotope fractionation as evidence ==\nThe root mean square thermal velocity (<math>v_{th}</math>) of an atomic species is\n\n<math>v_{th} = \\sqrt{\\frac{3kT}{m}}</math>\n\nwhere <math>k</math> is the [[Boltzmann constant]], <math>T</math>is the temperature, and <math>m</math>is the mass of the species. Lighter molecules or atoms will therefore be moving faster than heavier molecules or atoms at the same temperature. This is why atomic hydrogen escapes preferentially from an atmosphere and also explains why the ratio of lighter to heavier [[isotope]]s of atmospheric particles can indicate hydrodynamic escape.\n\nSpecifically, the ratio of different noble gas isotopes  (<sup>20</sup>[[Neon|Ne]]/<sup>22</sup>Ne, <sup>36</sup>[[Argon|Ar]]/<sup>38</sup>Ar, <sup>78,80,82,83,86</sup>[[Krypton|Kr]]/<sup>84</sup>Kr, <sup>124,126,128,129,131,132,134,136</sup>[[Xenon|Xe]]/<sup>130</sup>Xe) or [[Isotopes of hydrogen|hydrogen isotopes]] ([[Deuterium|D]]/H) can be compared to solar levels to indicate likelihood of hydrodynamic escape in the atmospheric evolution. Ratios larger or smaller than compared with that in the sun or [[CI chondrite]]s, which are used as proxy for the sun, indicate that significant hydrodynamic escape has occurred since the formation of the planet. Since lighter atoms preferentially escape, we expect smaller ratios for the noble gas isotopes (or a larger D/H) correspond to a greater likelihood of hydrodynamic escape, as indicated in the table.\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+Isotopic fractionation in Venus, Earth, and Mars <ref>{{Cite journal|last=Pepin|first=Robert O.|date=1991-07-01|title=On the origin and early evolution of terrestrial planet atmospheres and meteoritic volatiles|journal=Icarus|volume=92|issue=1|pages=2\u201379|doi=10.1016/0019-1035(91)90036-S|issn=0019-1035}}</ref>\n!Source\n!36Ar/38Ar\n!20Ne/22Ne\n!82Kr/84Kr\n!128Xe/130Xe\n|-\n|Sun\n|5.8\n|13.7\n|20.501\n|50.873\n|-\n|CI chondrites\n|5.3\u00b10.05\n|8.9\u00b11.3\n|20.149\u00b10.080\n|50.73\u00b10.38\n|-\n|Venus\n|5.56\u00b10.62\n|11.8\u00b10.7\n| --\n| --\n|-\n|Earth\n|5.320\u00b10.002\n|9.800\u00b10.08\n|20.217\u00b10.021\n|47.146\u00b10.047\n|-\n|Mars\n|4.1\u00b10.2\n|10.1\u00b10.7\n|20.54\u00b10.20\n|47.67\u00b11.03\n|}\nMatching these ratios can also be used to validate or verify computational models seeking to describe atmospheric evolution. This method has also been used to determine the escape of oxygen relative to hydrogen in early atmospheres.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Hunten|first=Donald M.|last2=Pepin|first2=Robert O.|last3=Walker|first3=James C. G.|date=1987-03-01|title=Mass fractionation in hydrodynamic escape|journal=Icarus|volume=69|issue=3|pages=532\u2013549|doi=10.1016/0019-1035(87)90022-4|issn=0019-1035|hdl=2027.42/26796}}</ref>\n\n== Examples ==\n[[Exoplanets]] that are extremely close to their parent star, such as [[hot Jupiter]]s can experience significant hydrodynamic escape<ref>{{cite journal | citeseerx = 10.1.1.122.9085 | first1 = Feng | title = Transonic Hydrodynamic Escape of Hydrogen from Extrasolar Planetary Atmospheres | last1 = Tian | first2 = Owen B. | last2 = Toon | first3 = Alexander A. | last3 = Pavlov | first4 =  H. | last4 = de Sterck | journal = The Astrophysical Journal | volume = 621 | issue = 2 | pages = 1049\u20131060 | date = March 10, 2005 | doi=10.1086/427204|bibcode = 2005ApJ...621.1049T }}</ref><ref>{{cite journal | arxiv = 1001.4851 | title = Mass-radius relationships for exoplanets | journal = The Astrophysical Journal | volume = 744 | issue = 1 | pages = 59 | first1 = Damian C. | last1 = Swift | first2 =  Jon | last2 = Eggert | first3 = Damien G. | last3 = Hicks | first4 = Sebastien | last4 = Hamel | first5 = Kyle | last5 = Caspersen | first6 = Eric | last6 = Schwegler | first7 = Gilbert W. | last7 =Collins |bibcode = 2012ApJ...744...59S |doi = 10.1088/0004-637X/744/1/59 | year = 2012 }}</ref> to the point where the star \"burns off\" their atmosphere upon which they cease to be [[gas giant]]s and are left with just the core, at which point they would be called [[Chthonian planet]]s. Hydrodynamic escape has been observed for exoplanets close to their host star, including the [[hot Jupiters]] [[HD 209458b]].<ref>{{Cite journal|title=Vidal-Madjar et al., Oxygen and Carbon in HD 209458b|doi=10.1086/383347}}</ref>\n\nWithin a stellar lifetime, the solar flux may change. Younger stars produce more EUV, and the early protoatmospheres of [[Earth]], [[Mars]], and [[Venus]] likely underwent hydrodynamic escape, which accounts for the noble gas isotope fractionation present in their atmospheres.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Gillmann|first=C\u00e9dric|last2=Chassefi\u00e8re|first2=Eric|last3=Lognonn\u00e9|first3=Philippe|date=2009-09-15|title=A consistent picture of early hydrodynamic escape of Venus atmosphere explaining present Ne and Ar isotopic ratios and low oxygen atmospheric content|journal=Earth and Planetary Science Letters|volume=286|issue=3|pages=503\u2013513|doi=10.1016/j.epsl.2009.07.016|issn=0012-821X}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Atmosphere]]\n", "text_old": "'''Hydrodynamic escape''' refers to a thermal [[atmospheric escape]] mechanism that can lead to the escape of heavier atoms of a [[planet]]ary [[Celestial body atmosphere|atmosphere]] through numerous collisions with lighter atoms.\n[[File:Hydrodynamic_escape.png|thumb|Schematic of hydrodynamic escape. Energy from solar radiation is deposited in a thin shell. This energy heats the atmosphere, which then begins to expand. This expansion continues into the vacuum of space, accelerating as it goes until it escapes.]]\n\n== Description ==\nHydrodynamic escape occurs if there is a strong thermally driven atmospheric escape of light atoms which, through drag effects (collisions), also drive off heavier atoms.<ref>{{cite book |title= Giant planets of our solar system: an introduction |last= Irwin|first=Patrick G. J. |authorlink= |date= 2006|publisher= Birkh\u00e4user |location= |isbn=3-540-31317-6 |page=58 |url= https://books.google.com/books?id=D6HZKSKg6P0C|accessdate= 22 Dec 2009}}</ref> The heaviest species of atom that can be removed in this manner is called the ''cross-over'' mass.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Hunten|first=Donald M.|last2=Pepin|first2=Robert O.|last3=Walker|first3=James C. G.|date=1987-03-01|title=Mass fractionation in hydrodynamic escape|journal=Icarus|volume=69|issue=3|pages=532\u2013549|doi=10.1016/0019-1035(87)90022-4|issn=0019-1035|hdl=2027.42/26796}}</ref>\n\nIn order to maintain a significant hydrodynamic escape, a large source of energy at a certain altitude is required.  [[Soft X-ray]] or [[extreme ultraviolet]] radiation, momentum transfer from impacting [[meteoroid]]s or [[asteroid]]s, or the heat input from planetary [[Accretion (astrophysics)|accretion processes]]<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=RaJdy3_VINQC|title=Planetary sciences|last=Pater|first=Imke De|author2=Jack Jonathan Lissauer|date=2001|publisher=[[Cambridge University Press]]|isbn=0-521-48219-4|location=|page=129|authorlink=|accessdate=}}</ref> may provide the requisite energy for hydrodynamic escape.\n\n== Calculations ==\nEstimating the rate of hydrodynamic escape is important in analyzing both the history and current state of a planet's atmosphere. In 1981, Watson et al published<ref name=\":12\">{{Cite journal|last=Watson|first=Andrew J.|last2=Donahue|first2=Thomas M.|last3=Walker|first3=James C.G.|date=November 1981|title=The dynamics of a rapidly escaping atmosphere: Applications to the evolution of Earth and Venus|journal=Icarus|volume=48|issue=2|pages=150\u2013166|doi=10.1016/0019-1035(81)90101-9|hdl=2027.42/24204|url=https://deepblue.lib.umich.edu/bitstream/2027.42/24204/1/0000463.pdf}}</ref> calculations that describe energy-limited escape, where all incoming energy is balanced by escape to space. Recent numerical simulations on exoplanets have suggested that this calculation overestimates the hydrodynamic flux by 20 - 100 times.<sup>[30]</sup> However, as an special case and upper limit approximation on the atmospheric escape, it is worth noting here.\n\nHydrodynamic escape [[flux]] (<math>\\Phi</math>, [m<math>^{-2}</math>s<math>^{-1}</math>]) in an energy-limited escape can calculated, assuming (1) an atmosphere composed of non-[[Viscosity|viscous]], (2) constant molecular weight gas, with (3) [[Isotropy|isotropic]] pressure, (4) fixed temperature, (5) perfect XUV absorption, and that (6) pressure decreases to zero as distance from the planet increases.<ref name=\":12\"/>\n\n<math>\\Phi=\\frac{F_{XUV} R_p R_{XUV}^2}{G M_p}</math>\n\nwhere <math>F_{XUV}</math> is the [[photon]] flux [J m<math>^{-2}</math>s<math>^{-1}</math>] over the wavelengths of interest, <math>R_p</math> is the radius of the planet, <math>G</math>is the [[gravitational constant]], <math>M_p</math> is the mass of the planet, and <math>R_{XUV}</math> is the effective radius where the XUV absorption occurs. Corrections to this model have been proposed over the years to account for the [[Roche lobe]] of a planet and efficiency in absorbing photon flux.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Erkaev|first=N. V.|last2=Kulikov|first2=Yu. N.|last3=Lammer|first3=H.|last4=Selsis|first4=F.|last5=Langmayr|first5=D.|last6=Jaritz|first6=G. F.|last7=Biernat|first7=H. K.|date=September 2007|title=Roche lobe effects on the atmospheric loss from \"Hot Jupiters\"|journal=Astronomy & Astrophysics|volume=472|issue=1|pages=329\u2013334|doi=10.1051/0004-6361:20066929|issn=0004-6361}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Lecavelier des Etangs|first=A.|date=January 2007|title=A diagram to determine the evaporation status of extrasolar planets|journal=Astronomy & Astrophysics|volume=461|issue=3|pages=1185\u20131193|doi=10.1051/0004-6361:20065014|issn=0004-6361|arxiv=astro-ph/0609744}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Tian|first=Feng|last2=G\u00fcdel|first2=Manuel|last3=Johnstone|first3=Colin P.|last4=Lammer|first4=Helmut|last5=Luger|first5=Rodrigo|last6=Odert|first6=Petra|date=April 2018|title=Water Loss from Young Planets|journal=Space Science Reviews|volume=214|issue=3|doi=10.1007/s11214-018-0490-9|issn=0038-6308}}</ref>\n\nHowever, as computational power has improved, increasingly sophisticated models have emerged, incorporating [[radiative transfer]], [[photochemistry]], and [[hydrodynamics]] that provide better estimates of hydrodynamic escape.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Owen|first=James E.|date=2019-05-30|title=Atmospheric Escape and the Evolution of Close-In Exoplanets|journal=Annual Review of Earth and Planetary Sciences|volume=47|issue=1|pages=67\u201390|doi=10.1146/annurev-earth-053018-060246|issn=0084-6597|arxiv=1807.07609}}</ref>\n\n== Isotope fractionation as evidence ==\nThe root mean square thermal velocity (<math>v_{th}</math>) of an atomic species is\n\n<math>v_{th} = \\sqrt{\\frac{3kT}{m}}</math>\n\nwhere <math>k</math> is the [[Boltzmann constant]], <math>T</math>is the temperature, and <math>m</math>is the mass of the species. Lighter molecules or atoms will therefore be moving faster than heavier molecules or atoms at the same temperature. This is why atomic hydrogen escapes preferentially from an atmosphere and also explains why the ratio of lighter to heavier [[isotope]]s of atmospheric particles can indicate hydrodynamic escape.\n\nSpecifically, the ratio of different noble gas isotopes  (<sup>20</sup>[[Neon|Ne]]/<sup>22</sup>Ne, <sup>36</sup>[[Argon|Ar]]/<sup>38</sup>Ar, <sup>78,80,82,83,86</sup>[[Krypton|Kr]]/<sup>84</sup>Kr, <sup>124,126,128,129,131,132,134,136</sup>[[Xenon|Xe]]/<sup>130</sup>Xe) or [[Isotopes of hydrogen|hydrogen isotopes]] ([[Deuterium|D]]/H) can be compared to solar levels to indicate likelihood of hydrodynamic escape in the atmospheric evolution. Ratios larger or smaller than compared with that in the sun or [[CI chondrite]]s, which are used as proxy for the sun, indicate that significant hydrodynamic escape has occurred since the formation of the planet. Since lighter atoms preferentially escape, we expect smaller ratios for the noble gas isotopes (or a larger D/H) correspond to a greater likelihood of hydrodynamic escape, as indicated in the table.\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+Isotopic fractionation in Venus, Earth, and Mars <ref>{{Cite journal|last=Pepin|first=Robert O.|date=1991-07-01|title=On the origin and early evolution of terrestrial planet atmospheres and meteoritic volatiles|journal=Icarus|volume=92|issue=1|pages=2\u201379|doi=10.1016/0019-1035(91)90036-S|issn=0019-1035}}</ref>\n!Source\n!36Ar/38Ar\n!20Ne/22Ne\n!82Kr/84Kr\n!128Xe/130Xe\n|-\n|Sun\n|5.8\n|13.7\n|20.501\n|50.873\n|-\n|CI chondrites\n|5.3\u00b10.05\n|8.9\u00b11.3\n|20.149\u00b10.080\n|50.73\u00b10.38\n|-\n|Venus\n|5.56\u00b10.62\n|11.8\u00b10.7\n| --\n| --\n|-\n|Earth\n|5.320\u00b10.002\n|9.800\u00b10.08\n|20.217\u00b10.021\n|47.146\u00b10.047\n|-\n|Mars\n|4.1\u00b10.2\n|10.1\u00b10.7\n|20.54\u00b10.20\n|47.67\u00b11.03\n|}\nMatching these ratios can also be used to validate or verify computational models seeking to describe atmospheric evolution. This method has also been used to determine the escape of oxygen relative to hydrogen in early atmospheres.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Hunten|first=Donald M.|last2=Pepin|first2=Robert O.|last3=Walker|first3=James C. G.|date=1987-03-01|title=Mass fractionation in hydrodynamic escape|journal=Icarus|volume=69|issue=3|pages=532\u2013549|doi=10.1016/0019-1035(87)90022-4|issn=0019-1035|hdl=2027.42/26796}}</ref>\n\n== Examples ==\n[[Exoplanets]] that are extremely close to their parent star, such as [[hot Jupiter]]s can experience significant hydrodynamic escape<ref>{{cite journal | citeseerx = 10.1.1.122.9085 | first1 = Feng | title = Transonic Hydrodynamic Escape of Hydrogen from Extrasolar Planetary Atmospheres | last1 = Tian | first2 = Owen B. | last2 = Toon | first3 = Alexander A. | last3 = Pavlov | first4 =  H. | last4 = de Sterck | journal = The Astrophysical Journal | volume = 621 | issue = 2 | pages = 1049\u20131060 | date = March 10, 2005 | doi=10.1086/427204|bibcode = 2005ApJ...621.1049T }}</ref><ref>{{cite journal | arxiv = 1001.4851 | title = Mass-radius relationships for exoplanets | journal = The Astrophysical Journal | volume = 744 | issue = 1 | pages = 59 | first1 = Damian C. | last1 = Swift | first2 =  Jon | last2 = Eggert | first3 = Damien G. | last3 = Hicks | first4 = Sebastien | last4 = Hamel | first5 = Kyle | last5 = Caspersen | first6 = Eric | last6 = Schwegler | first7 = Gilbert W. | last7 =Collins |bibcode = 2012ApJ...744...59S |doi = 10.1088/0004-637X/744/1/59 | year = 2012 }}</ref> to the point where the star \"burns off\" their atmosphere upon which they cease to be [[gas giant]]s and are left with just the core, at which point they would be called [[Chthonian planet]]s. Hydrodynamic escape has been observed for exoplanets close to their host star, including the [[hot Jupiters]] [[HD 209458b]].<ref>{{Cite journal|title=Vidal-Madjar et al., Oxygen and Carbon in HD 209458b|doi=10.1086/383347}}</ref>\n\nWithin a stellar lifetime, the solar flux may change. Younger stars produce more EUV, and the early protoatmospheres of [[Earth]], [[Mars]], and [[Venus]] likely underwent hydrodynamic escape, which accounts for the noble gas isotope fractionation present in their atmospheres.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Gillmann|first=C\u00e9dric|last2=Chassefi\u00e8re|first2=Eric|last3=Lognonn\u00e9|first3=Philippe|date=2009-09-15|title=A consistent picture of early hydrodynamic escape of Venus atmosphere explaining present Ne and Ar isotopic ratios and low oxygen atmospheric content|journal=Earth and Planetary Science Letters|volume=286|issue=3|pages=503\u2013513|doi=10.1016/j.epsl.2009.07.016|issn=0012-821X}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Atmosphere]]\n", "name_user": "Iridescent", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eCalculations:Cleanup andtypo fixing,typo(s) fixed: et al \u2192 et al.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hydrodynamic_escape"}
{"title_page": "Varicocele", "text_new": "{{Infobox medical condition (new) \n| name            = Varicocele\n| image           = Varikozele2.jpg\n| caption         = Varicocele on the person's left testicle. Notice the swelling and slight enlargement of the left testicle, which is marked by an arrow.\n| field           = [[Urology]]\n| pronounce       = {{IPAc-en|\u02c8|v|\u00e6r|\u1d7b|k|o\u028a|\u02cc|s|i\u02d0|l|,_|-|k|\u0259|-}}{{refn|{{MerriamWebsterDictionary|accessdate=2016-01-21|Varicocele}}}}{{refn|{{OxfordDictionaries.com|accessdate=2016-01-21|Varicocele}}}}\n| symptoms        =\n| complications   =\n| onset           = \n| duration        = \n| types           = \n| causes          = \n| risks           = \n| diagnosis       = \n| differential    = \n| prevention      = \n| treatment       = \n| medication      = \n| prognosis       = \n| frequency       = \n| deaths          = \n}}\nA '''varicocele''' is an abnormal enlargement of the [[pampiniform venous plexus]] in the scrotum. This plexus of [[vein]]s drains [[blood]] from the [[testicle]]s back to the heart. The [[blood vessel|vessel]]s originate in the abdomen and course down through the [[inguinal canal]] as part of the [[spermatic cord]] on their way to the [[testis]]. Varicoceles occur in around 15% to 20% of all men.<ref name=\"WhiteKimMobley2019\">{{cite web |last1=White |first1=Wesley M. |last2=Kim |first2=Edward David |last3=Mobley |first3=Joe D |title=Varicocele: Epidemiology |url=https://emedicine.medscape.com/article/438591-overview#a7 |website=[[Medscape]] |accessdate=18 September 2019 |language=English |date=2 January 2019 |quote=Although varicoceles appear in approximately 20% of the general male population, they are much more common in the subfertile population (40%).}}</ref><ref name=KupisDobronski2015/> However, Varicocele is also present in nearly 40% of all infertile men<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://progyny.com/education/male-infertility/varicoceles/|title=Varicocele and Male Infertility|website=Progyny|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-07}}</ref>. The incidence of varicocele increase with age.\n\n==Signs and symptoms==\nVaricocele might be noticed as soft lumps, usually above the testicle and mostly on the left side of the [[scrotum]].<ref name=NHSlumps/> Right-sided and bilateral varicocele does also occur. Men with varicocele can feel symptoms of pain or heaviness in their [[scrotum]].<ref name=NHSlumps>{{cite web|title=Testicular lumps and swellings - Causes - NHS Choices|url=http://www.nhs.uk/Conditions/Testicular-lumps-benign/Pages/Causes.aspx|publisher=NHS Choices|date=7 October 2014}}</ref> Large varicoceles present as plexus of veins and may be described as \"bag of worms\".<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Cannarella |first1=Rossella |last2=Calogero |first2=Aldo E. |last3=Condorelli |first3=Rosita A. |last4=Giacone |first4=Filippo |last5=Aversa |first5=Antonio |last6=La Vignera |first6=Sandro |title=Management and Treatment of Varicocele in Children and Adolescents: An Endocrinologic Perspective |journal=Journal of Clinical Medicine |date=8 September 2019 |volume=9 |issue=8 |doi=10.3390/jcm8091410 |pmid=31500355 |url=https://www.mdpi.com/2077-0383/8/9/1410/htm |accessdate=20 January 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |last1=Leslie |first1=Stephen W. |last2=Sajjad |first2=Hussain |last3=Siref |first3=Larry E. |title=Varicocele |date=7 October 2019 |publisher=StatPearls [Internet] |url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK448113/ |accessdate=20 January 2020}}</ref> Varicocele is sometimes discovered when investigating the cause of [[male infertility]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Low sperm count|url=http://www.nhs.uk/conditions/low-sperm-count/Pages/Introduction.aspx|publisher=NHS Choices|date=2 August 2016}}</ref><ref name=Baazeem2011/>\n\n==Cause==\n[[File:Gray1147.png|thumb|Cross section showing the pampiniform venus plexus]]\nThere are three main theories as to the anatomical cause; the first has to do with the geometry of the veins, wherein the vein on the left side connects to the larger outflowing vein at a right angle, which tends to fail; the second is that valves that are supposed to prevent backflow fail (venous insufficiency); the third is due to excessive pressure in upstream arteries, created by [[nutcracker syndrome]].<ref name=\"Eisenberg\">{{Cite journal|last=Eisenberg|first=Michael L.|last2=Lipshultz|first2=Larry I.|date=2011-01-01|title=Varicocele-induced infertility: Newer insights into its pathophysiology|journal= Indian Journal of Urology|volume=27|issue=1|pages=58\u201364|doi=10.4103/0970-1591.78428|issn=0970-1591|pmc=3114589|pmid=21716891}}</ref>\n\n==Pathophysiology==\nOften the greatest concern with respect to varicocele is its effect on male fertility. The relationship between varicocele and infertility is unclear. Some men with the condition are fertile, some have sperm that are normal in shape and move normally but are compromised in function, and some have sperm with abnormal shapes or that do not move well.<ref name=Eisenberg/> Theories as to how varicocele affects sperm function include damage via excess heat caused by the blood pooling and [[Reactive oxygen species|oxidative stress]] on sperm.<ref name=KupisDobronski2015>{{cite journal|last1=Kupis|first1=\u0141|last2=Dobro\u0144ski|first2=PA|last3=Radziszewski|first3=P|title=Varicocele as a source of male infertility - current treatment techniques.|journal=Central European Journal of Urology|date=2015|volume=68|issue=3|pages=365\u201370|doi=10.5173/ceju.2015.642|pmid=26568883|pmc=4643713}}</ref><ref name=Eisenberg/><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Hayden|first=Russell P.|last2=Tanrikut|first2=Cigdem|date=2016-05-01|title=Testosterone and Varicocele|journal=The Urologic Clinics of North America|volume=43|issue=2|pages=223\u2013232|doi=10.1016/j.ucl.2016.01.009|issn=1558-318X|pmid=27132580}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Dabaja|first=Ali|last2=Wosnitzer|first2=Matthew|last3=Goldstein|first3=Marc|date=2013-08-01|title=Varicocele and hypogonadism|journal=Current Urology Reports|volume=14|issue=4|pages=309\u2013314|doi=10.1007/s11934-013-0339-4|issn=1534-6285|pmid=23754533}}</ref>\n\n[[Smoking|Tobacco smoking]] and mutations in the gene expressing [[glutathione S-transferase Mu 1]] both put men at risk for infertility; these factors may also exacerbate the risk that varicocele will affect fertility.<ref name=Eisenberg/>\n\n==Diagnosis==\nFollowing discovery of the sign of swelling comprising a mass, varicocele can be confirmed with [[scrotal ultrasound]], which will show dilation of the vessels of the pampiniform plexus to be greater than 2&nbsp;mm.<ref>{{cite book |last=Salam |first=MA |date=2013 |title=Principles and Practice of Urology |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=efG8AQAAQBAJ&printsec=frontcover#v=onepage&q&f=false |location=New Delhi 110 002, India |publisher=Jaypee Brothers Medical Publishers |page=752 |isbn=978-93-5025-260-4}}</ref>\n\n<gallery mode=\"packed\" heights=\"175px\">\nFile:trans varicocele.tif|Varicocele in ultrasound (left: testicle)\nFile:Varicocele.png|Varicocele\n</gallery>\n\n==Treatment==\n[[File:Sew up wound after varicocele surgery.jpg|thumb|Sewn up wound after varicocele surgery]]\nThe two most common surgical approaches are [[retroperitoneal]] (abdominal using [[laparoscopic surgery]]), infrainguinal/subinguinal (below the groin) and [[Groin|inguinal]] (groin using [[percutaneous]] [[embolization]]).<ref name=KupisDobronski2015/> Possible complications of this procedure include [[hematoma]] (bleeding into tissues), [[hydrocele]] (accumulation of fluid around the affected testicle), [[infection]], or injury to the scrotal tissue or structures. In addition, injury to the artery that supplies the testicle may occur, resulting in a loss of a testicle.<ref name=KupisDobronski2015/>\n\nWhether having varicocele surgery or embolization improves male fertility is controversial, as good clinical data is lacking.<ref name=Baazeem2011/>  There is tentative evidence that varicocelectomy may improve fertility in those with obvious findings and abnormal sperm;<ref name=KupisDobronski2015/> however, this has a [[number needed to treat]] of 7 for varicocelectomy and 17 for embolization.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Kroese|first=A. C. J.|last2=Lange|first2=N. M. de|last3=Collins|first3=J. A.|last4=Evers|first4=J. L. H.|date=2013-07-01|title=Varicocele surgery, new evidence|journal=Human Reproduction Update|volume=19|issue=4|pages=317|doi=10.1093/humupd/dmt004|pmid=23515200}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|last2=Yue|first2=Huanxun|last3=Yamaguchi|first3=Kohei|last4=Okada|first4=Keisuke|last5=Matsushita|first5=Kei|last6=Ando|first6=Makoto|last7=Chiba|first7=Koji|last8=Fujisawa|first8=Masato|year=2012|title=Effect of surgical repair on testosterone production in infertile men with varicocele: A meta-analysis|journal=International Journal of Urology|volume=19|issue=2|pages=149\u201354|doi=10.1111/j.1442-2042.2011.02890.x|pmid=22059526|last1=Li|first1=Fuping}}</ref> There are also studies showing that the regular surgery has no significant effect on infertility.<ref name=Baazeem2011>{{Cite journal|last=Baazeem|first=Abdulaziz|last2=Belzile|first2=Eric|last3=Ciampi|first3=Antonio|last4=Dohle|first4=Gert|last5=Jarvi|first5=Keith|last6=Salonia|first6=Andrea|last7=Weidner|first7=Wolfgang|last8=Zini|first8=Armand|date=2011-10-01|title=Varicocele and male factor infertility treatment: a new meta-analysis and review of the role of varicocele repair|journal=European Urology|volume=60|issue=4|pages=796\u2013808|doi=10.1016/j.eururo.2011.06.018|pmid=21733620}}</ref>  A 2012 [[Cochrane Database Systematic Reviews|Cochrane review]] found tentative but unclear evidence of improved fertility among males treated for varicocele.<ref name=Cochrane2012>{{cite journal|last1=Kroese|first1=AC|last2=de Lange|first2=NM|last3=Collins|first3=J|last4=Evers|first4=JL|title=Surgery or embolization for varicoceles in subfertile men.|journal=The Cochrane Database of Systematic Reviews|date=17 October 2012|volume=10|pages=CD000479|pmid=23076888|doi=10.1002/14651858.CD000479.pub5}}</ref> Evidence for [[sclerotherapy]] is unclear as of 2015.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Macleod |first1=R |last2=Biyani |first2=CS |last3=Cartledge |first3=J |last4=Eardley |first4=I |title=Varicocele. |journal=BMJ clinical evidence |date=13 July 2015 |volume=2015 |pmid=26168774}}</ref>\n\n==Epidemiology==\nAround 15% to 20% of all adult males, up to 35% to 40% of men who are evaluated for male infertility, and around 80% of men who are infertile due to some other cause, have varicocele.<ref name=\"WhiteKimMobley2019\"/><ref name=KupisDobronski2015/><ref name=Baazeem2011/>\n{{-}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Medical resources\n| ICD10          = {{ICD10|I|86|1|i|80}} \n| ICD9           = {{ICD9|456.4}} \n| ICDO           = \n| OMIM           = \n| MedlinePlus    = 001284 \n| eMedicineSubj  = radio \n| eMedicineTopic = 739 \n| DiseasesDB     = 13731 \n| MeshID         = D014646 \n}}\n\n{{Portal bar|Medicine}}\n{{Vascular diseases}}\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Andrology]]\n[[Category:Male genital disorders]]\n[[Category:Scrotum]]\n[[Category:Vascular diseases]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox medical condition (new) \n| name            = Varicocele\n| image           = Varikozele2.jpg\n| caption         = Varicocele on the person's left testicle. Notice the swelling and slight enlargement of the left testicle, which is marked by an arrow.\n| field           = [[Urology]]\n| pronounce       = {{IPAc-en|\u02c8|v|\u00e6r|\u1d7b|k|o\u028a|\u02cc|s|i\u02d0|l|,_|-|k|\u0259|-}}{{refn|{{MerriamWebsterDictionary|accessdate=2016-01-21|Varicocele}}}}{{refn|{{OxfordDictionaries.com|accessdate=2016-01-21|Varicocele}}}}\n| symptoms        =\n| complications   =\n| onset           = \n| duration        = \n| types           = \n| causes          = \n| risks           = \n| diagnosis       = \n| differential    = \n| prevention      = \n| treatment       = \n| medication      = \n| prognosis       = \n| frequency       = \n| deaths          = \n}}\nA '''varicocele''' is an abnormal enlargement of the [[pampiniform venous plexus]] in the scrotum. This plexus of [[vein]]s drains [[blood]] from the [[testicle]]s back to the heart. The [[blood vessel|vessel]]s originate in the abdomen and course down through the [[inguinal canal]] as part of the [[spermatic cord]] on their way to the [[testis]]. Varicoceles occur in around 15% to 20% of all men.<ref name=\"WhiteKimMobley2019\">{{cite web |last1=White |first1=Wesley M. |last2=Kim |first2=Edward David |last3=Mobley |first3=Joe D |title=Varicocele: Epidemiology |url=https://emedicine.medscape.com/article/438591-overview#a7 |website=[[Medscape]] |accessdate=18 September 2019 |language=English |date=2 January 2019 |quote=Although varicoceles appear in approximately 20% of the general male population, they are much more common in the subfertile population (40%).}}</ref><ref name=KupisDobronski2015/> The incidence of varicocele increase with age.\n\n==Signs and symptoms==\nVaricocele might be noticed as soft lumps, usually above the testicle and mostly on the left side of the [[scrotum]].<ref name=NHSlumps/> Right-sided and bilateral varicocele does also occur. Men with varicocele can feel symptoms of pain or heaviness in their [[scrotum]].<ref name=NHSlumps>{{cite web|title=Testicular lumps and swellings - Causes - NHS Choices|url=http://www.nhs.uk/Conditions/Testicular-lumps-benign/Pages/Causes.aspx|publisher=NHS Choices|date=7 October 2014}}</ref> Large varicoceles present as plexus of veins and may be described as \"bag of worms\".<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Cannarella |first1=Rossella |last2=Calogero |first2=Aldo E. |last3=Condorelli |first3=Rosita A. |last4=Giacone |first4=Filippo |last5=Aversa |first5=Antonio |last6=La Vignera |first6=Sandro |title=Management and Treatment of Varicocele in Children and Adolescents: An Endocrinologic Perspective |journal=Journal of Clinical Medicine |date=8 September 2019 |volume=9 |issue=8 |doi=10.3390/jcm8091410 |pmid=31500355 |url=https://www.mdpi.com/2077-0383/8/9/1410/htm |accessdate=20 January 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |last1=Leslie |first1=Stephen W. |last2=Sajjad |first2=Hussain |last3=Siref |first3=Larry E. |title=Varicocele |date=7 October 2019 |publisher=StatPearls [Internet] |url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK448113/ |accessdate=20 January 2020}}</ref> Varicocele is sometimes discovered when investigating the cause of [[male infertility]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Low sperm count|url=http://www.nhs.uk/conditions/low-sperm-count/Pages/Introduction.aspx|publisher=NHS Choices|date=2 August 2016}}</ref><ref name=Baazeem2011/>\n\n==Cause==\n[[File:Gray1147.png|thumb|Cross section showing the pampiniform venus plexus]]\nThere are three main theories as to the anatomical cause; the first has to do with the geometry of the veins, wherein the vein on the left side connects to the larger outflowing vein at a right angle, which tends to fail; the second is that valves that are supposed to prevent backflow fail (venous insufficiency); the third is due to excessive pressure in upstream arteries, created by [[nutcracker syndrome]].<ref name=\"Eisenberg\">{{Cite journal|last=Eisenberg|first=Michael L.|last2=Lipshultz|first2=Larry I.|date=2011-01-01|title=Varicocele-induced infertility: Newer insights into its pathophysiology|journal= Indian Journal of Urology|volume=27|issue=1|pages=58\u201364|doi=10.4103/0970-1591.78428|issn=0970-1591|pmc=3114589|pmid=21716891}}</ref>\n\n==Pathophysiology==\nOften the greatest concern with respect to varicocele is its effect on male fertility. The relationship between varicocele and infertility is unclear. Some men with the condition are fertile, some have sperm that are normal in shape and move normally but are compromised in function, and some have sperm with abnormal shapes or that do not move well.<ref name=Eisenberg/> Theories as to how varicocele affects sperm function include damage via excess heat caused by the blood pooling and [[Reactive oxygen species|oxidative stress]] on sperm.<ref name=KupisDobronski2015>{{cite journal|last1=Kupis|first1=\u0141|last2=Dobro\u0144ski|first2=PA|last3=Radziszewski|first3=P|title=Varicocele as a source of male infertility - current treatment techniques.|journal=Central European Journal of Urology|date=2015|volume=68|issue=3|pages=365\u201370|doi=10.5173/ceju.2015.642|pmid=26568883|pmc=4643713}}</ref><ref name=Eisenberg/><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Hayden|first=Russell P.|last2=Tanrikut|first2=Cigdem|date=2016-05-01|title=Testosterone and Varicocele|journal=The Urologic Clinics of North America|volume=43|issue=2|pages=223\u2013232|doi=10.1016/j.ucl.2016.01.009|issn=1558-318X|pmid=27132580}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Dabaja|first=Ali|last2=Wosnitzer|first2=Matthew|last3=Goldstein|first3=Marc|date=2013-08-01|title=Varicocele and hypogonadism|journal=Current Urology Reports|volume=14|issue=4|pages=309\u2013314|doi=10.1007/s11934-013-0339-4|issn=1534-6285|pmid=23754533}}</ref>\n\n[[Smoking|Tobacco smoking]] and mutations in the gene expressing [[glutathione S-transferase Mu 1]] both put men at risk for infertility; these factors may also exacerbate the risk that varicocele will affect fertility.<ref name=Eisenberg/>\n\n==Diagnosis==\nFollowing discovery of the sign of swelling comprising a mass, varicocele can be confirmed with [[scrotal ultrasound]], which will show dilation of the vessels of the pampiniform plexus to be greater than 2&nbsp;mm.<ref>{{cite book |last=Salam |first=MA |date=2013 |title=Principles and Practice of Urology |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=efG8AQAAQBAJ&printsec=frontcover#v=onepage&q&f=false |location=New Delhi 110 002, India |publisher=Jaypee Brothers Medical Publishers |page=752 |isbn=978-93-5025-260-4}}</ref>\n\n<gallery mode=\"packed\" heights=\"175px\">\nFile:trans varicocele.tif|Varicocele in ultrasound (left: testicle)\nFile:Varicocele.png|Varicocele\n</gallery>\n\n==Treatment==\n[[File:Sew up wound after varicocele surgery.jpg|thumb|Sewn up wound after varicocele surgery]]\nThe two most common surgical approaches are [[retroperitoneal]] (abdominal using [[laparoscopic surgery]]), infrainguinal/subinguinal (below the groin) and [[Groin|inguinal]] (groin using [[percutaneous]] [[embolization]]).<ref name=KupisDobronski2015/> Possible complications of this procedure include [[hematoma]] (bleeding into tissues), [[hydrocele]] (accumulation of fluid around the affected testicle), [[infection]], or injury to the scrotal tissue or structures. In addition, injury to the artery that supplies the testicle may occur, resulting in a loss of a testicle.<ref name=KupisDobronski2015/>\n\nWhether having varicocele surgery or embolization improves male fertility is controversial, as good clinical data is lacking.<ref name=Baazeem2011/>  There is tentative evidence that varicocelectomy may improve fertility in those with obvious findings and abnormal sperm;<ref name=KupisDobronski2015/> however, this has a [[number needed to treat]] of 7 for varicocelectomy and 17 for embolization.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Kroese|first=A. C. J.|last2=Lange|first2=N. M. de|last3=Collins|first3=J. A.|last4=Evers|first4=J. L. H.|date=2013-07-01|title=Varicocele surgery, new evidence|journal=Human Reproduction Update|volume=19|issue=4|pages=317|doi=10.1093/humupd/dmt004|pmid=23515200}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|last2=Yue|first2=Huanxun|last3=Yamaguchi|first3=Kohei|last4=Okada|first4=Keisuke|last5=Matsushita|first5=Kei|last6=Ando|first6=Makoto|last7=Chiba|first7=Koji|last8=Fujisawa|first8=Masato|year=2012|title=Effect of surgical repair on testosterone production in infertile men with varicocele: A meta-analysis|journal=International Journal of Urology|volume=19|issue=2|pages=149\u201354|doi=10.1111/j.1442-2042.2011.02890.x|pmid=22059526|last1=Li|first1=Fuping}}</ref> There are also studies showing that the regular surgery has no significant effect on infertility.<ref name=Baazeem2011>{{Cite journal|last=Baazeem|first=Abdulaziz|last2=Belzile|first2=Eric|last3=Ciampi|first3=Antonio|last4=Dohle|first4=Gert|last5=Jarvi|first5=Keith|last6=Salonia|first6=Andrea|last7=Weidner|first7=Wolfgang|last8=Zini|first8=Armand|date=2011-10-01|title=Varicocele and male factor infertility treatment: a new meta-analysis and review of the role of varicocele repair|journal=European Urology|volume=60|issue=4|pages=796\u2013808|doi=10.1016/j.eururo.2011.06.018|pmid=21733620}}</ref>  A 2012 [[Cochrane Database Systematic Reviews|Cochrane review]] found tentative but unclear evidence of improved fertility among males treated for varicocele.<ref name=Cochrane2012>{{cite journal|last1=Kroese|first1=AC|last2=de Lange|first2=NM|last3=Collins|first3=J|last4=Evers|first4=JL|title=Surgery or embolization for varicoceles in subfertile men.|journal=The Cochrane Database of Systematic Reviews|date=17 October 2012|volume=10|pages=CD000479|pmid=23076888|doi=10.1002/14651858.CD000479.pub5}}</ref> Evidence for [[sclerotherapy]] is unclear as of 2015.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Macleod |first1=R |last2=Biyani |first2=CS |last3=Cartledge |first3=J |last4=Eardley |first4=I |title=Varicocele. |journal=BMJ clinical evidence |date=13 July 2015 |volume=2015 |pmid=26168774}}</ref>\n\n==Epidemiology==\nAround 15% to 20% of all adult males, up to 35% to 40% of men who are evaluated for male infertility, and around 80% of men who are infertile due to some other cause, have varicocele.<ref name=\"WhiteKimMobley2019\"/><ref name=KupisDobronski2015/><ref name=Baazeem2011/>\n{{-}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Medical resources\n| ICD10          = {{ICD10|I|86|1|i|80}} \n| ICD9           = {{ICD9|456.4}} \n| ICDO           = \n| OMIM           = \n| MedlinePlus    = 001284 \n| eMedicineSubj  = radio \n| eMedicineTopic = 739 \n| DiseasesDB     = 13731 \n| MeshID         = D014646 \n}}\n\n{{Portal bar|Medicine}}\n{{Vascular diseases}}\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Andrology]]\n[[Category:Male genital disorders]]\n[[Category:Scrotum]]\n[[Category:Vascular diseases]]\n", "name_user": "Mrseriouswag", "label": "safe", "comment": "Added details.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Varicocele"}
{"title_page": "Jos\u00e9 Bedia Vald\u00e9s", "text_new": "{{BLP sources|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox person\n|name=Jos\u00e9 Braulio Bedia Vald\u00e9s\n|image=\n|caption=\n|birth_date={{Birth date and age|1959|1|13|mf=y}}\n|birth_place=Havana, Cuba\n|death_date=\n|death_place=\n}}\n[[File:Jose Bedia - 'Senor de la Noche', acrylic on canvas, 1992, HAA.jpg|thumb|right|300px|''Se\u00f1or de la Noche'', acrylic on canvas by '''Jos\u00e9 Bedia Vald\u00e9s''', 1992, [[Honolulu Museum of Art]]]]\n'''Jos\u00e9 Braulio Bedia Vald\u00e9s''' (born January 13, 1959 in [[Havana]], [[Cuba]])<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.museodeartecarrillogil.com/coleccion/artistas-de-la-coleccion/jose-bedia|title=Jose Bedia|last=|first=|date=|website=Museo de Arte Carrillo Gil|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-07}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://americanart.si.edu/artist/jose-bedia-18580|title=Jos\u00e9 Bedia {{!}} Smithsonian American Art Museum|website=americanart.si.edu|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-07}}</ref>is a [[Cuba]]n painter.\n\nBedia studied at the [[Escuela Nacional de Bellas Artes \"San Alejandro\"]] and then finished his art studies at the [[Instituto Superior de Arte]] in Havana.\n\n==Selected individual exhibitions==\n*1989 \u2013 ''Final del Centauro'' \u2013 [[Castillo de la Real Fuerza]], Havana, Cuba\n*1994 \u2013 ''Jos\u00e9 Bedia: De Donde Vengo'' \u2013 Institute of Contemporary Art, University of Pennsylvania\n*2004 \u2013 ''Estremecimientos'' \u2013 Museo Extreme\u00f1o e Iberoamericano de Arte Contemporaneo (MEIAC), Badajoz, Spain\n*September 18, 2011 \u2013 January 8, 2012 \u2013 ''Transcultural Pilgrim: Three Decades of Work by Jos\u00e9 Bedia'' \u2013 Fowler Museum, UCLA\n\n==Collective exhibitions==\nIn 1978 he began participating with other artists in several collective exhibitions. In 1980 he conformed the exhibition ''XIX Premi Internacional de Dibuix [[Joan Mir\u00f3]]''. Fundaci\u00f3 Joan Mir\u00f3, Centre d\u2019Estudis d\u2019Art Contemporani, Parc de Montjuic, [[Barcelona]],Spain; ''Los nov\u00edsimos cubanos. [[Grupo Volumen I]]'' was a significant exhibitionn that took place at The Signs Gallery, New York. He was selected to participate in the Cubans exhibition in the 1st and 2nd Havana Biennial [[Bienal de La Habana]], Museo Nacional de Bellas Artes. In 1990 he was in the XLIV Exposizione Internazionale d\u2019Arte, Biennale di Venezia, [[Venice]], [[Italy]]. In 1994, his work was exhibited at \"InSite94: A Binational Exhibition of Installation and Site Specific Art\" San Diego Train Station, San Diego, California. Most recently in 2001 his pieces were part of ''Inside and Out, Contemporary Sculpture, Video and Installations'', Bass Museum of Art, IV Bienal del Caribe y Centroam\u00e9rica, Museo de Arte Moderno, Santo Domingo, Dominican Republic. In 2013 Bedia participated in the collective exhibit ''Drapetomania: Exposicion Homenaje a [[Grupo Antillano]]'' in Santiago de Cuba.\n\n==Awards==\nHe has obtained several awards for his artistic work:\n* 1982 \u2013 First Prize in the ''\"Sal\u00f3n Paisaje\u201982\"'', [[Museo Nacional de Bellas Artes de La Habana]], Havana, Cuba.\n* 1993 \u2013 [[International Guggenheim Fellowship]], [[New York City]].\n* 1988 \u2013 Distinction for the National Culture, Cuban Council of State, Havana, Cuba.\n\n==Collections==\nHis pieces can be found in the permanent collections of:\n* George Adams Gallery, [[New York City]]\n* [[Arkansas Art Center]], [[Little Rock]], [[Arkansas]]\n* [[Birmingham Museum of Art]], [[Birmingham, Alabama|Birmingham]], [[Alabama]]\n* [[Cantor Arts Center]], [[Stanford University]], [[California]]\n* Galer\u00eda Nina Menocal in [[M\u00e9xico]]\n* [[Honolulu Museum of Art]], [[Honolulu, Hawaii]]\n* [[Loeb Art Center]], [[Vassar College]], [[Poughkeepsie (town), New York|Poughkeepsie]], [[New York (state)|New York]]\n* Ludwig Forum f\u00fcr Internationale Kunst, [[Aachen]], [[Germany]]\n* [[Perez Art Museum Miami]], [[Miami]], [[Florida]]\n* [[Porin Taidemuseo]], [[Finland]]\n* [[Wifredo Lam|Centro Wifredo Lam]], [[Havana]]\n* [[Museo Nacional de Bellas Artes de La Habana]], [[Havana]]\n* [[NSU Art Museum, Fort Lauderdale]], [[Florida]]\n*de la Cruz Collection, Florida\n*[[Kendall Art Center]], Miami, Florida\n*[[Frost Art Museum]], Miami, Florida\n\n==Bibliography==\n* Jose Bedia Works 19778-2006, Turner, 2007\n* Jose Bedia: Transcultural Pilgrim, Bettelheim and Berlo, 2012\n* Jos\u00e9 Bedia: Estremecimientos, Omar-Pascual Castillo, 2004\n*Jose Viegas; ''Memoria: Artes Visuales Cubanas Del Siglo Xx''; (California International Arts 2004); {{ISBN|978-0-917571-12-1}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.aaa.si.edu/collections/interviews/oral-history-interview-jos-bedia-5419 Oral history interview with Jos\u00e9 Bedia, 1998, February 13] from the Smithsonian [[Archives of American Art]]\n*[http://fowler.ucla.edu/exhibitions/transcultural-pilgrim-bedia Transcultural Pilgrim: Three Decades of Work by Jos\u00e9 Bedia] at the Fowler Museum, UCLA\n*[http://www.Josebedia.com josebedia.com] (Personal Website of Jose Bedia)\n\n{{Portal|Cuba}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n== References ==\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Bedia Valdes, Jose Braulio}}\n[[Category:Cuban contemporary artists]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:1959 births]]\n[[Category:Cuban painters]]\n[[Category:Guggenheim Fellows]]\n", "text_old": "{{BLP sources|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox person\n|name=Jos\u00e9 Braulio Bedia Vald\u00e9s\n|image=\n|caption=\n|birth_date={{Birth date and age|1959|1|13|mf=y}}\n|birth_place=Havana, Cuba\n|death_date=\n|death_place=\n}}\n[[File:Jose Bedia - 'Senor de la Noche', acrylic on canvas, 1992, HAA.jpg|thumb|right|300px|''Se\u00f1or de la Noche'', acrylic on canvas by '''Jos\u00e9 Bedia Vald\u00e9s''', 1992, [[Honolulu Museum of Art]]]]\n'''Jos\u00e9 Braulio Bedia Vald\u00e9s''' (born January 13, 1959 in [[Havana]], [[Cuba]])<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.museodeartecarrillogil.com/coleccion/artistas-de-la-coleccion/jose-bedia|title=Jose Bedia|last=|first=|date=|website=Museo de Arte Carrillo Gil|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-07}}</ref> is a [[Cuba]]n painter.\n\nBedia studied at the [[Escuela Nacional de Bellas Artes \"San Alejandro\"]] and then finished his art studies at the [[Instituto Superior de Arte]] in Havana.\n\n==Selected individual exhibitions==\n*1989 \u2013 ''Final del Centauro'' \u2013 [[Castillo de la Real Fuerza]], Havana, Cuba\n*1994 \u2013 ''Jos\u00e9 Bedia: De Donde Vengo'' \u2013 Institute of Contemporary Art, University of Pennsylvania\n*2004 \u2013 ''Estremecimientos'' \u2013 Museo Extreme\u00f1o e Iberoamericano de Arte Contemporaneo (MEIAC), Badajoz, Spain\n*September 18, 2011 \u2013 January 8, 2012 \u2013 ''Transcultural Pilgrim: Three Decades of Work by Jos\u00e9 Bedia'' \u2013 Fowler Museum, UCLA\n\n==Collective exhibitions==\nIn 1978 he began participating with other artists in several collective exhibitions. In 1980 he conformed the exhibition ''XIX Premi Internacional de Dibuix [[Joan Mir\u00f3]]''. Fundaci\u00f3 Joan Mir\u00f3, Centre d\u2019Estudis d\u2019Art Contemporani, Parc de Montjuic, [[Barcelona]],Spain; ''Los nov\u00edsimos cubanos. [[Grupo Volumen I]]'' was a significant exhibitionn that took place at The Signs Gallery, New York. He was selected to participate in the Cubans exhibition in the 1st and 2nd Havana Biennial [[Bienal de La Habana]], Museo Nacional de Bellas Artes. In 1990 he was in the XLIV Exposizione Internazionale d\u2019Arte, Biennale di Venezia, [[Venice]], [[Italy]]. In 1994, his work was exhibited at \"InSite94: A Binational Exhibition of Installation and Site Specific Art\" San Diego Train Station, San Diego, California. Most recently in 2001 his pieces were part of ''Inside and Out, Contemporary Sculpture, Video and Installations'', Bass Museum of Art, IV Bienal del Caribe y Centroam\u00e9rica, Museo de Arte Moderno, Santo Domingo, Dominican Republic. In 2013 Bedia participated in the collective exhibit ''Drapetomania: Exposicion Homenaje a [[Grupo Antillano]]'' in Santiago de Cuba.\n\n==Awards==\nHe has obtained several awards for his artistic work:\n* 1982 \u2013 First Prize in the ''\"Sal\u00f3n Paisaje\u201982\"'', [[Museo Nacional de Bellas Artes de La Habana]], Havana, Cuba.\n* 1993 \u2013 [[International Guggenheim Fellowship]], [[New York City]].\n* 1988 \u2013 Distinction for the National Culture, Cuban Council of State, Havana, Cuba.\n\n==Collections==\nHis pieces can be found in the permanent collections of:\n* George Adams Gallery, [[New York City]]\n* [[Arkansas Art Center]], [[Little Rock]], [[Arkansas]]\n* [[Birmingham Museum of Art]], [[Birmingham, Alabama|Birmingham]], [[Alabama]]\n* [[Cantor Arts Center]], [[Stanford University]], [[California]]\n* Galer\u00eda Nina Menocal in [[M\u00e9xico]]\n* [[Honolulu Museum of Art]], [[Honolulu, Hawaii]]\n* [[Loeb Art Center]], [[Vassar College]], [[Poughkeepsie (town), New York|Poughkeepsie]], [[New York (state)|New York]]\n* Ludwig Forum f\u00fcr Internationale Kunst, [[Aachen]], [[Germany]]\n* [[Perez Art Museum Miami]], [[Miami]], [[Florida]]\n* [[Porin Taidemuseo]], [[Finland]]\n* [[Wifredo Lam|Centro Wifredo Lam]], [[Havana]]\n* [[Museo Nacional de Bellas Artes de La Habana]], [[Havana]]\n* [[NSU Art Museum, Fort Lauderdale]], [[Florida]]\n*de la Cruz Collection, Florida\n*[[Kendall Art Center]], Miami, Florida\n*[[Frost Art Museum]], Miami, Florida\n\n==Bibliography==\n* Jose Bedia Works 19778-2006, Turner, 2007\n* Jose Bedia: Transcultural Pilgrim, Bettelheim and Berlo, 2012\n* Jos\u00e9 Bedia: Estremecimientos, Omar-Pascual Castillo, 2004\n*Jose Viegas; ''Memoria: Artes Visuales Cubanas Del Siglo Xx''; (California International Arts 2004); {{ISBN|978-0-917571-12-1}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.aaa.si.edu/collections/interviews/oral-history-interview-jos-bedia-5419 Oral history interview with Jos\u00e9 Bedia, 1998, February 13] from the Smithsonian [[Archives of American Art]]\n*[http://fowler.ucla.edu/exhibitions/transcultural-pilgrim-bedia Transcultural Pilgrim: Three Decades of Work by Jos\u00e9 Bedia] at the Fowler Museum, UCLA\n*[http://www.Josebedia.com josebedia.com] (Personal Website of Jose Bedia)\n\n{{Portal|Cuba}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n== References ==\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Bedia Valdes, Jose Braulio}}\n[[Category:Cuban contemporary artists]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:1959 births]]\n[[Category:Cuban painters]]\n[[Category:Guggenheim Fellows]]\n", "name_user": "BoriquaZurdo", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jos%C3%A9_Bedia_Vald%C3%A9s"}
{"title_page": "Hard Normal Daddy", "text_new": "{{Infobox album\n| name         = Hard Normal Daddy\n| type         = [[Album]]\n| artist       = [[Squarepusher]]\n| cover        = Squarepusher.hardnormaldaddy.jpg\n| alt          = \n| released     = {{start date|1997|04|28|df=yes}}\n| recorded     = \n| venue        = \n| studio       = \n| genre        = {{hlist|[[Drill 'n' bass]]|[[Intelligent dance music|IDM]]|[[Jazz Fusion]]}}\n| length       = {{duration|m=62|s=37}}\n| label        = [[Warp (record label)|Warp]]\n| producer     = [[Squarepusher|Tom Jenkinson]]\n| prev_title   = [[Port Rhombus EP]]\n| prev_year    = 1996\n| next_title   = [[Big Loada]]\n| next_year    = 1997\n| misc         = {{Singles\n | name        = Hard Normal Daddy\n | type        = album\n | single1     = [[Vic Acid]]\n | single1date = 31 March 1997\n}}\n}}\n\n'''''Hard Normal Daddy''''' is the second studio album by English [[electronic music]]ian Tom Jenkinson under the alias [[Squarepusher]], released on 28 April 1997. The album was Jenkinson's first studio album as Squarepusher for [[Warp (record label)|Warp]]. A single for the track \"[[Vic Acid]]\" was released in 1997 prior to the album's release.\n\nThe album has received praise since its release including a five star review from [[AllMusic]] and being listed as one of the best albums of the year by ''[[The Wire (magazine)|The Wire]]'' and the ''[[NME]]''. ''[[Stylus Magazine]]'' referred to the album in 2003 as Squarepusher's \"masterpiece\".\n\n==Production==\nTom Jenkinson was offered to sign to [[Ninja Tune]], [[Rephlex Records]], [[R&S Records]] and [[Warp (record label)|Warp]]. Jenkinson eventually chose Warp as he was more interested in the label's music.<ref name=\"psf\">{{cite web|url=http://www.furious.com/perfect/squarepusher.html|work=[[Perfect Sound Forever (magazine)|Perfect Sound Forever]]|author=Gross, Jason|title=Squarepusher Interview|date=January 1999|accessdate=4 July 2013}}</ref>\n\n==Style==\n''[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]]'' cited the album's musical style as an example of the [[drill 'n' bass]] subgenre, described by the online music database [[AllMusic]] as a version of [[drum and bass]] that warped \"old midtempo beats and breaks into a frenzied, experimental potpourri of low-attention-span electronic music.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.allmusic.com/style/drillnbass-ma0000012008|publisher=[[AllMusic]]|title=Drill'n'bass|accessdate=25 January 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"bestidm\"/>\n\nThe ''Palm Beach Newspaper'' described the album as [[jazz fusion]] influenced, describing its contents as \"Lyrical, complicated keyboard riffs, dense, churning beats, nimble, melodic fretless bass \u2013 add in a saxophone, and you'd have the drum 'n' bass equivalent of [[Weather Report]].\"<ref>{{cite newspaper|newspaper=Palm Beach Newspaper|title=Fusion an Inspiration for Many Musicians|date=12 April 1998|page=6J}}</ref> Tom Jenkinson has stated that his music on ''Hard Normal Daddy'' was not influenced by [[jazz fusion]], but more [[funk music|funk]] oriented music like [[Herbie Hancock]]'s [[Death Wish (soundtrack)|''Death Wish soundtrack]] and cop show themes.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.redbullmusicacademy.com/magazine/squarepusher-interview|publisher=[[Red Bull Music Academy]]|title=Interview: Squarepusher|author=Blanning, Lisa|date=8 August 2012|accessdate=4 July 2013}}</ref>\n\n== Artwork ==\nThe visuals for ''Hard Normal Daddy'' were done by Johnny Clayton. Clayton told Jenkinson to take inspiration from his hometown of [[Chelmsford|Chelmsford, Essex]]. Given a camera, he took photos of the town including sheds where illegal raves were held and the local park which were used on the CD packaging, and a run-down gas container that features on the album cover<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.vice.com/en_uk/article/ae9ed5/warp-25-johnny-clayton-interview|title=We Spoke to Johnny Clayton, the Guy Who Made Aphex Twin Creep Us Out|last=|first=|date=24 July 2014|website=VICE|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200407195548/https://www.vice.com/en_uk/article/ae9ed5/warp-25-johnny-clayton-interview|archive-date=7 Apr 2020|access-date=7 Apr 2020}}</ref>. In late 2018, that gas chamber was demolished<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.reddit.com/r/electronicmusic/comments/9hp7kt/the_gas_container_from_the_cover_of_squarepushers/|title=r/electronicmusic - The gas container from the cover of Squarepusher\u2019s Hard Normal Daddy is being demolished today|website=reddit|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-07}}</ref>, over twenty years after the release of ''Hard Normal Daddy''.\n\n==Release==\n''Hard Normal Daddy'' was released by [[Warp Records]] on 28 April 1997. It was released on [[compact disc]], [[vinyl records|double vinyl]], [[audio cassette|cassette]] and [[Music download|digital download]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://warp.net/records/releases/squarepusher/hard-normal-daddy|title=Warp / Records / Releases / Squarepusher / Hard Normal Daddy|publisher=[[Warp Records]]|accessdate=4 July 2013}}</ref> and was dedicated to the Chelmsford rave scene. A single was released for the album for the track \"[[Vic Acid]]\" on 31 March 1997 by Warp on compact disc and 12-inch vinyl.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.allmusic.com/album/vic-acid-mw0000911274/releases|publisher=AllMusic|title=Vic Acid \u2013 Squarepusher: Releases|accessdate=4 July 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.allmusic.com/album/vic-acid-mw0000911274|publisher=AllMusic|title=Vic Acid \u2013 Squarepusher|accessdate=4 July 2013|author=DiGravina, Tim}}</ref>\n\n==Reception==\n{{Album reviews\n|rev1 = [[AllMusic]]\n|rev1Score = {{Rating|5|5}}<ref name=\"allmusic\" />\n|rev2 = ''[[Muzik]]''\n|rev2Score = 7/10<ref name=\"muzik\">{{cite journal|title=Squarepusher: Hard Normal Daddy (Warp)|work=[[Muzik]]|issue=24|date=May 1997|author=Howe, Rupert|page=112}}</ref>\n|rev3 = ''[[The Rolling Stone Album Guide]]''\n|rev3Score = {{rating|3.5|5}}{{sfn|Wolk|2004|p=773}}}}\nIn a contemporary review, ''[[Muzik]]'' critic Rupert Howe praised ''Hard Normal Daddy'' as an album of \"style, wit and crafty ingenuity\", albeit one that \"isn't always quite as clever as it would like to think it is\".<ref name=\"muzik\"/> Retrospectively, Sean Cooper of AllMusic gave ''Hard Normal Daddy'' five out of five stars, comparing it favourably to similar releases from the music labels [[Spymania]] and [[Rephlex]] and describing the album as \"substantially cleaner and more thought out than previous releases\" from those labels.<ref name=\"allmusic\">{{cite web|url=http://www.allmusic.com/album/hard-normal-daddy-mw0000017249|publisher=[[AllMusic]]|title=Hard Normal Daddy \u2013 Squarepusher|author=Cooper, Sean|accessdate=4 July 2013}}</ref> The music was also praised for not \"simply relying on the shock value of \"tripping-over-myself\" drum programming and light-speed fretless bass noodling.\"<ref name=\"allmusic\" /> In 2003, Todd Burns of ''[[Stylus Magazine]]'' referred to the album as Squarepusher's \"masterpiece\" and wrote that Squarepusher \"refrains from such mind numbing repetition and put down his most accomplished work to that point.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.stylusmagazine.com/articles/on_second_thought/squarepusher-hard-normal-daddy.htm|work=[[Stylus Magazine]]|title=Squarepusher \u2013 Hard Normal Daddy|accessdate=4 July 2013|date=1 September 2003|author=Burns, Todd|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171023010613/http://www.stylusmagazine.com/articles/on_second_thought/squarepusher-hard-normal-daddy.htm|archivedate=23 October 2017}}</ref> ''[[The Wire (magazine)|The Wire]]'' placed the album on their list of the best albums of 1998.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://thewire.co.uk/archive/1997-rewind|work=[[The Wire (magazine)|The Wire]]|title=1997 Rewind|date=December 2007|access-date=5 July 2013|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130621224243/http://thewire.co.uk/archive/1997-rewind|archive-date=21 June 2013|df=}}</ref> The ''[[NME]]'' placed the album at number 34 on their list of best albums of 1997.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nme.com/bestalbumsandtracksoftheyear/1997|work=[[NME]]|title=Albums and Tracks of the Year for 1997|accessdate=20 April 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn 1999, Jenkinson referred to the music on his albums ''[[Feed Me Weird Things]]'' and ''Hard Normal Daddy'' as \"already beginning to sound a bit... It sort of reminds me of being a bit younger in a way. It's a bit more (of a) naive approach, a bit more fresh. The sound as well. I've gotten better production.\" and \"I still REALLY like it. I like my stuff 'cause I only ever end up with tracks that I really, really like. It always appeals to me. There's only about four tracks that I've done which I don't really like. The rest of them I like.\"<ref name=\"psf\" /> Writing in 2004's ''[[The Rolling Stone Album Guide|The New Rolling Stone Album Guide]]'', critic [[Douglas Wolk]] wrote that on the album, Jenkinson \"either sublimates [his beats] to tunes like 'Cooper's World' that approximate an early-'70s sort of [[jazz-funk|funk-jazz]] hybrid, or makes them carry delirious tracks like 'Chin Hippy' with almost no help\".{{sfn|Wolk|2004|p=773}} In 2017, ''[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]]'' placed ''Hard Normal Daddy'' at number 24 on its list of \"The 50 Best IDM Albums of All Time\".<ref name=\"bestidm\">{{cite web|url=https://pitchfork.com/features/lists-and-guides/10011-the-50-best-idm-albums-of-all-time/?page=3|title=The 50 Best IDM Albums of All Time|work=[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]]|date=24 January 2017|accessdate=25 January 2017|page=3}}</ref>\n\n==Track listing==\nAll songs composed by [[Squarepusher|Tom Jenkinson]].<ref name=\"allmusic\" />\n{{Track list\n|title1 = Cooper's World  \n|length1 = 5:09\n|title2 = Beep Street  \n|length2 = 6:37\n|title3 = Rustic Raver  \n|length3 = 5:08\n|title4 = Anirog D9  \n|length4 = 1:11\n|title5 = Chin Hippy  \n|length5 = 3:16\n|title6 = Papalon  \n|length6 = 8:10\n|title7 = E8 Boogie  \n|length7 = 8:13\n|title8 = Fat Controller  \n|length8 = 5:38\n|title9 = [[Vic Acid]]  \n|length9 = 3:07\n|title10 = Male Pill Part 13  \n|length10 = 8:38\n|title11 = Rat/P's and Q's   \n|length11 = 4:33\n|title12 = Rebus  \n|length12 = 2:47\n}}\n\n==Credits==\n* [[Squarepusher|Tom Jenkinson]] \u2013 composition\n* Frank Arkwright \u2013 [[audio mastering|mastering]]\n* John Clayton \u2013 visuals\n\n==Charts==\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders sortable\" style=\"text-align:center;\" border=\"1\"\n!scope=\"col\"| Chart (1997)\n!scope=\"col\"| Peak<br />position\n|-\n{{Album chart|UK|115|M|url=https://www.zobbel.de/cluk/CLUK_S.HTM|title=Chart Log UK: DJ S \u2013 The System Of Life|publisher=Zobbel.de|accessdate=23 August 2019|rowheader=true}}\n|}\n\n==See also==\n* [[1997 in music]]\n* [[Music of the United Kingdom (1990s)]]\n\n== References ==\n\n===Footnotes===\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n===Sources===\n{{Refbegin}}\n* {{cite book\n |last=Wolk\n |first=Douglas\n |authorlink=Douglas Wolk\n |editor1-last=Brackett \n |editor1-first=Nathan \n |editor2-last=Hoard\n |editor2-first=Christian\n |chapter=Squarepusher\n |title=[[The Rolling Stone Album Guide|The New Rolling Stone Album Guide]]\n |publisher=[[Simon & Schuster]]\n |edition=4th\n |isbn=0743201698\n |year=2004\n |ref=harv\n}}\n\n{{Squarepusher}}\n\n[[Category:Squarepusher albums]]\n[[Category:Warp (record label) albums]]\n[[Category:1997 albums]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox album\n| name         = Hard Normal Daddy\n| type         = [[Album]]\n| artist       = [[Squarepusher]]\n| cover        = Squarepusher.hardnormaldaddy.jpg\n| alt          = \n| released     = {{start date|1997|04|28|df=yes}}\n| recorded     = \n| venue        = \n| studio       = \n| genre        = {{hlist|[[Drill 'n' bass]]|[[Intelligent dance music|IDM]]|[[Jazz Fusion]]}}\n| length       = {{duration|m=62|s=37}}\n| label        = [[Warp (record label)|Warp]]\n| producer     = [[Squarepusher|Tom Jenkinson]]\n| prev_title   = [[Port Rhombus EP]]\n| prev_year    = 1996\n| next_title   = [[Big Loada]]\n| next_year    = 1997\n| misc         = {{Singles\n | name        = Hard Normal Daddy\n | type        = album\n | single1     = [[Vic Acid]]\n | single1date = 31 March 1997\n}}\n}}\n\n'''''Hard Normal Daddy''''' is the second studio album by English [[electronic music]]ian Tom Jenkinson under the alias [[Squarepusher]], released on 28 April 1997. The album was Jenkinson's first studio album as Squarepusher for [[Warp (record label)|Warp]]. A single for the track \"[[Vic Acid]]\" was released in 1997 prior to the album's release.\n\nThe album has received praise since its release including a five star review from [[AllMusic]] and being listed as one of the best albums of the year by ''[[The Wire (magazine)|The Wire]]'' and the ''[[NME]]''. ''[[Stylus Magazine]]'' referred to the album in 2003 as Squarepusher's \"masterpiece\".\n\n==Production==\nTom Jenkinson was offered to sign to [[Ninja Tune]], [[Rephlex Records]], [[R&S Records]] and [[Warp (record label)|Warp]]. Jenkinson eventually chose Warp as he was more interested in the label's music.<ref name=\"psf\">{{cite web|url=http://www.furious.com/perfect/squarepusher.html|work=[[Perfect Sound Forever (magazine)|Perfect Sound Forever]]|author=Gross, Jason|title=Squarepusher Interview|date=January 1999|accessdate=4 July 2013}}</ref>\n\n==Style==\n''[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]]'' cited the album's musical style as an example of the [[drill 'n' bass]] subgenre, described by the online music database [[AllMusic]] as a version of [[drum and bass]] that warped \"old midtempo beats and breaks into a frenzied, experimental potpourri of low-attention-span electronic music.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.allmusic.com/style/drillnbass-ma0000012008|publisher=[[AllMusic]]|title=Drill'n'bass|accessdate=25 January 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"bestidm\"/>\n\nThe ''Palm Beach Newspaper'' described the album as [[jazz fusion]] influenced, describing its contents as \"Lyrical, complicated keyboard riffs, dense, churning beats, nimble, melodic fretless bass \u2013 add in a saxophone, and you'd have the drum 'n' bass equivalent of [[Weather Report]].\"<ref>{{cite newspaper|newspaper=Palm Beach Newspaper|title=Fusion an Inspiration for Many Musicians|date=12 April 1998|page=6J}}</ref> Tom Jenkinson has stated that his music on ''Hard Normal Daddy'' was not influenced by [[jazz fusion]], but more [[funk music|funk]] oriented music like [[Herbie Hancock]]'s [[Death Wish (soundtrack)|''Death Wish soundtrack]] and cop show themes.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.redbullmusicacademy.com/magazine/squarepusher-interview|publisher=[[Red Bull Music Academy]]|title=Interview: Squarepusher|author=Blanning, Lisa|date=8 August 2012|accessdate=4 July 2013}}</ref>\n\n== Artwork ==\nThe visuals for ''Hard Normal Daddy'' were done by Johnny Clayton. Clayton told Jenkinson to take inspiration from his hometown of [[Chelmsford|Chelmsford, Essex]]. Given a camera, he took photos of the town including sheds where illegal raves were held and the local park which on the CD packaging, and a run-down gas container that features on the album cover<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.vice.com/en_uk/article/ae9ed5/warp-25-johnny-clayton-interview|title=We Spoke to Johnny Clayton, the Guy Who Made Aphex Twin Creep Us Out|last=|first=|date=24 July 2014|website=VICE|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200407195548/https://www.vice.com/en_uk/article/ae9ed5/warp-25-johnny-clayton-interview|archive-date=7 Apr 2020|access-date=7 Apr 2020}}</ref>. In late 2018, that gas chamber was demolished<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.reddit.com/r/electronicmusic/comments/9hp7kt/the_gas_container_from_the_cover_of_squarepushers/|title=r/electronicmusic - The gas container from the cover of Squarepusher\u2019s Hard Normal Daddy is being demolished today|website=reddit|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-07}}</ref>, over twenty years after the release of ''Hard Normal Daddy''.\n\n==Release==\n''Hard Normal Daddy'' was released by [[Warp Records]] on 28 April 1997. It was released on [[compact disc]], [[vinyl records|double vinyl]], [[audio cassette|cassette]] and [[Music download|digital download]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://warp.net/records/releases/squarepusher/hard-normal-daddy|title=Warp / Records / Releases / Squarepusher / Hard Normal Daddy|publisher=[[Warp Records]]|accessdate=4 July 2013}}</ref> and was dedicated to the Chelmsford rave scene. A single was released for the album for the track \"[[Vic Acid]]\" on 31 March 1997 by Warp on compact disc and 12-inch vinyl.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.allmusic.com/album/vic-acid-mw0000911274/releases|publisher=AllMusic|title=Vic Acid \u2013 Squarepusher: Releases|accessdate=4 July 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.allmusic.com/album/vic-acid-mw0000911274|publisher=AllMusic|title=Vic Acid \u2013 Squarepusher|accessdate=4 July 2013|author=DiGravina, Tim}}</ref>\n\n==Reception==\n{{Album reviews\n|rev1 = [[AllMusic]]\n|rev1Score = {{Rating|5|5}}<ref name=\"allmusic\" />\n|rev2 = ''[[Muzik]]''\n|rev2Score = 7/10<ref name=\"muzik\">{{cite journal|title=Squarepusher: Hard Normal Daddy (Warp)|work=[[Muzik]]|issue=24|date=May 1997|author=Howe, Rupert|page=112}}</ref>\n|rev3 = ''[[The Rolling Stone Album Guide]]''\n|rev3Score = {{rating|3.5|5}}{{sfn|Wolk|2004|p=773}}}}\nIn a contemporary review, ''[[Muzik]]'' critic Rupert Howe praised ''Hard Normal Daddy'' as an album of \"style, wit and crafty ingenuity\", albeit one that \"isn't always quite as clever as it would like to think it is\".<ref name=\"muzik\"/> Retrospectively, Sean Cooper of AllMusic gave ''Hard Normal Daddy'' five out of five stars, comparing it favourably to similar releases from the music labels [[Spymania]] and [[Rephlex]] and describing the album as \"substantially cleaner and more thought out than previous releases\" from those labels.<ref name=\"allmusic\">{{cite web|url=http://www.allmusic.com/album/hard-normal-daddy-mw0000017249|publisher=[[AllMusic]]|title=Hard Normal Daddy \u2013 Squarepusher|author=Cooper, Sean|accessdate=4 July 2013}}</ref> The music was also praised for not \"simply relying on the shock value of \"tripping-over-myself\" drum programming and light-speed fretless bass noodling.\"<ref name=\"allmusic\" /> In 2003, Todd Burns of ''[[Stylus Magazine]]'' referred to the album as Squarepusher's \"masterpiece\" and wrote that Squarepusher \"refrains from such mind numbing repetition and put down his most accomplished work to that point.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.stylusmagazine.com/articles/on_second_thought/squarepusher-hard-normal-daddy.htm|work=[[Stylus Magazine]]|title=Squarepusher \u2013 Hard Normal Daddy|accessdate=4 July 2013|date=1 September 2003|author=Burns, Todd|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171023010613/http://www.stylusmagazine.com/articles/on_second_thought/squarepusher-hard-normal-daddy.htm|archivedate=23 October 2017}}</ref> ''[[The Wire (magazine)|The Wire]]'' placed the album on their list of the best albums of 1998.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://thewire.co.uk/archive/1997-rewind|work=[[The Wire (magazine)|The Wire]]|title=1997 Rewind|date=December 2007|access-date=5 July 2013|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130621224243/http://thewire.co.uk/archive/1997-rewind|archive-date=21 June 2013|df=}}</ref> The ''[[NME]]'' placed the album at number 34 on their list of best albums of 1997.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nme.com/bestalbumsandtracksoftheyear/1997|work=[[NME]]|title=Albums and Tracks of the Year for 1997|accessdate=20 April 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn 1999, Jenkinson referred to the music on his albums ''[[Feed Me Weird Things]]'' and ''Hard Normal Daddy'' as \"already beginning to sound a bit... It sort of reminds me of being a bit younger in a way. It's a bit more (of a) naive approach, a bit more fresh. The sound as well. I've gotten better production.\" and \"I still REALLY like it. I like my stuff 'cause I only ever end up with tracks that I really, really like. It always appeals to me. There's only about four tracks that I've done which I don't really like. The rest of them I like.\"<ref name=\"psf\" /> Writing in 2004's ''[[The Rolling Stone Album Guide|The New Rolling Stone Album Guide]]'', critic [[Douglas Wolk]] wrote that on the album, Jenkinson \"either sublimates [his beats] to tunes like 'Cooper's World' that approximate an early-'70s sort of [[jazz-funk|funk-jazz]] hybrid, or makes them carry delirious tracks like 'Chin Hippy' with almost no help\".{{sfn|Wolk|2004|p=773}} In 2017, ''[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]]'' placed ''Hard Normal Daddy'' at number 24 on its list of \"The 50 Best IDM Albums of All Time\".<ref name=\"bestidm\">{{cite web|url=https://pitchfork.com/features/lists-and-guides/10011-the-50-best-idm-albums-of-all-time/?page=3|title=The 50 Best IDM Albums of All Time|work=[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]]|date=24 January 2017|accessdate=25 January 2017|page=3}}</ref>\n\n==Track listing==\nAll songs composed by [[Squarepusher|Tom Jenkinson]].<ref name=\"allmusic\" />\n{{Track list\n|title1 = Cooper's World  \n|length1 = 5:09\n|title2 = Beep Street  \n|length2 = 6:37\n|title3 = Rustic Raver  \n|length3 = 5:08\n|title4 = Anirog D9  \n|length4 = 1:11\n|title5 = Chin Hippy  \n|length5 = 3:16\n|title6 = Papalon  \n|length6 = 8:10\n|title7 = E8 Boogie  \n|length7 = 8:13\n|title8 = Fat Controller  \n|length8 = 5:38\n|title9 = [[Vic Acid]]  \n|length9 = 3:07\n|title10 = Male Pill Part 13  \n|length10 = 8:38\n|title11 = Rat/P's and Q's   \n|length11 = 4:33\n|title12 = Rebus  \n|length12 = 2:47\n}}\n\n==Credits==\n* [[Squarepusher|Tom Jenkinson]] \u2013 composition\n* Frank Arkwright \u2013 [[audio mastering|mastering]]\n* John Clayton \u2013 visuals\n\n==Charts==\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders sortable\" style=\"text-align:center;\" border=\"1\"\n!scope=\"col\"| Chart (1997)\n!scope=\"col\"| Peak<br />position\n|-\n{{Album chart|UK|115|M|url=https://www.zobbel.de/cluk/CLUK_S.HTM|title=Chart Log UK: DJ S \u2013 The System Of Life|publisher=Zobbel.de|accessdate=23 August 2019|rowheader=true}}\n|}\n\n==See also==\n* [[1997 in music]]\n* [[Music of the United Kingdom (1990s)]]\n\n== References ==\n\n===Footnotes===\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n===Sources===\n{{Refbegin}}\n* {{cite book\n |last=Wolk\n |first=Douglas\n |authorlink=Douglas Wolk\n |editor1-last=Brackett \n |editor1-first=Nathan \n |editor2-last=Hoard\n |editor2-first=Christian\n |chapter=Squarepusher\n |title=[[The Rolling Stone Album Guide|The New Rolling Stone Album Guide]]\n |publisher=[[Simon & Schuster]]\n |edition=4th\n |isbn=0743201698\n |year=2004\n |ref=harv\n}}\n\n{{Squarepusher}}\n\n[[Category:Squarepusher albums]]\n[[Category:Warp (record label) albums]]\n[[Category:1997 albums]]\n", "name_user": "Winklon", "label": "safe", "comment": "Grammar", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hard_Normal_Daddy"}
{"title_page": "List of active separatist movements in Asia", "text_new": "{{short description|Wikimedia list article}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2018}}\n{{More citations needed|date=March 2019}}\nThis is a '''list of currently active [[Separatism|separatist]] movements in [[Asia]]'''. Separatism includes [[autonomism]] and [[secession]]ism. What is and is not considered an autonomist or secessionist movement is sometimes contentious. Entries on this list must meet three criteria:\n# They are active movements with current, active members.\n# They are seeking greater autonomy or self-determination for a geographic region (as opposed to personal autonomy).\n# They are the citizens/people of the conflicted area and doesn't come from other countries.\n\nUnder each region listed is one or more of the following:\n* ''De facto'' state: for regions with a ''[[de facto]]'' [[polity]]\n* Proposed state: proposed name for a seceding or anticipated [[sovereign state]]\n* Proposed autonomous area: for movements toward greater [[Autonomous area|autonomy for an area]] but not outright secession\n** ''De facto'' autonomous government: for governments with ''de facto'' autonomous control over a region\n** Government-in-exile: for a [[Government in exile|government based outside of the region in question]], with or without control\n** Political party (or parties): for [[Political party|political parties]] involved in a political system to push for autonomy or secession\n** Militant organisation(s): for [[irregular military|armed organisations]] or [[insurgency|insurgencies]]\n** Advocacy group(s): for [[Advocacy group|nonviolent, non-electoral, participatory entities]]\n** [[Ethnic]]/[[ethno-religious]]/[[racial]]/[[Regionalism (politics)|regional]]/[[Religious organization|religious]] group(s)\n{{TOC right}}\n\n== Azerbaijan ==\n{{Main|Nagorno-Karabakh War}}\n{{Further|List of active separatist movements in Europe}}\n\n;Breakaway state:\n\n{{Flag|Artsakh}}\n* Ethnic group: [[Armenians]]\n** De facto state: [[Republic of Artsakh]]\n** Government-in-exile: [[Azerbaijani Community of Nagorno-Karabakh]]\n\n== Bangladesh ==\n{{flagicon image|}} [[Bangabhumi]]\n* Ethnic group: [[Bengali Hindus]]\n** Region: South-western [[Bangladesh]]\n** Organisation: [[Banga Sena]]\n** Leader: Kalidas Baidya\n** Armed wing: Bir Banga\n\n{{flagicon image|Flag of Parbatya Chattagram Jana Samhati Samiti (PCJSS).png}} [[Chittagong Hill Tracts]]\n* Ethnic group: [[Jumma people]]\n** Political party: [[Parbatya Chattagram Jana Samhati Samiti|Parbotto Chottogram Jonshonghoti Shomiti]]\n* Further information: [[Chittagong Hill Tracts conflict]]\n\n{{flagicon image|}} [[Tripura]]\n** Ethnic group: [[Tripuri people|Tripuri]]\n** Organisation: [[All Tripura Tiger Force]]\n* Leader: [[Ranjit Debbarma]]\n\n{{flagicon image|Flag of Bnei Menashe.svg}} [[Zale'n-gam]]\n* Ethnic group: [[Kuki people]]\n** Region: Eastern borders of [[Bangladesh]] (primarily in parts of the [[Chittagong Hill Tracts]])\n** Organisation: [[Kuki National Organisation]]\n** Leaders: Pu S Haokip, Pu Letlam\n** Armed wing: [[Kuki National Army]]\n\n== China (Mainland China, Hong Kong, Macau) ==\n{{Main|Secession in China}}\n{{See also|Political status of Taiwan|One country, two systems|Ethnic minorities in China}}\n\n*'''The {{flagdeco|PRC}} [[People's Republic of China]] (China or PRC)''' is a state that is [[Foreign relations of China|recognised]] by 177 (out of 192 other) [[Member states of the United Nations|United Nations member states]] (as well as [[State of Palestine|Palestine]], an [[United Nations General Assembly observers|observer]]) as the [[China and the United Nations|sole legitimate government of China]]; the PRC represents China in the [[United Nations]] and is a [[Permanent members of the United Nations Security Council|permanent member of the United Nations Security Council]]. These states (that recognise the PRC's legitimacy) all recognise the [[Mainland|continental]] and island (e.g. [[Hainan]]) territory of \"[[mainland China]]\", which includes certain contentious regions such as [[Tibet]] and [[Xinjiang]], as being part of China (disregarding [[List of territorial disputes|border disputes]]). Mainland China does not include [[Hong Kong]], [[Macau]], and [[Taiwan]].\n**'''The''' {{flagdeco|PRC}} '''PRC's irredentist territorial claim to [[Taiwan]] as \"[[Taiwan Province, People's Republic of China]]\"''' \u2014 Many of the states that recognise the PRC's legitimacy have not clarified whether they specifically recognise China's [[Irredentism|irredentist]] [[Territorial dispute|territorial claim]] to the [[Geography of Taiwan|island of Taiwan]] and its [[List of islands of Taiwan|satellite islands]] (including [[Penghu]], [[Orchid Island]], [[Green Island, Taiwan|Green Island]], etc.), which it has [[History of Taiwan since 1945|never historically administered]]. China claims Taiwan as \"Taiwan Province, People's Republic of China\", but such a [[polity]] has never historically existed. Taiwan was designated a \"[[Provinces of China|province of China]]\" between 1887 and 1895 and a \"[[prefecture]] of [[Fujian|Fujian Province]]\" between 1684 and 1887, in both cases under the [[Qing dynasty]], an [[History of China|historical regime of China]] and the last Chinese [[Empire|imperial]] [[dynasty]]; the Qing dynasty [[Taiwanese indigenous peoples|never exercised absolute control]] over the entire island of Taiwan and its satellite islands.\n*'''The {{flagdeco|HKG}} [[Hong Kong|Hong Kong Special Administrative Region of the People's Republic of China]] (Hong Kong or Hong Kong SAR)''' is a highly autonomous territory whose sovereignty ultimately lies within China (PRC). Hong Kong's autonomy under a so-called [[One country, two systems|One Country Two Systems]] framework officially expires by 2047, at which point it is supposed to be fully integrated into China (PRC).\n*'''The {{flagdeco|MAC}} [[Macau|Macao (Macau) Special Administrative Region of the People's Republic of China]] (Macau/Macao or Macau/Macao SAR)''' is a highly autonomous territory whose sovereignty ultimately lies within China (PRC). Macau's autonomy under a so-called One Country Two Systems framework officially expires by 2049, at which point it is supposed to be fully integrated into China (PRC).\n\n===List of significant secessionist movements in China===\n* {{flagdeco|Taiwan}} [[Taiwan]] is not included in this list because it has never been governed by the [[China|People's Republic of China]].\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"font-size:100%\"\n|-\n| colspan=\"7\" bgcolor=\"#9acdff\" align=\"center\" |'''Significant Secessionist Movements in China'''\n|-\n! width=\"75\" |No.\n! width=\"225\" |Claimed Territory\n! width=\"100\" |Capital City\n! width=\"100\" |Area\n! width=\"100\" |Population\n! width=\"125\" |Ethnic Group\n! width=\"300\" |Primary Independence Movement\n|-\n| align=\"center\" |1 ||'''{{flagdeco|Tibet}} [[Tibet Autonomous Region|Xizang]] ([[Tibet]])'''||[[Lhasa]]|| align=\"center\" |2,500,000 || align=\"center\" |10,000,000 ||[[Tibetan people]]||[[Tibetan independence movement]]\n|-\n| align=\"center\" |2 ||'''{{flagdeco|East Turkestan}} [[Xinjiang]] ([[East Turkestan]])'''||[[\u00dcr\u00fcmqi]]|| align=\"center\" |1,700,000 || align=\"center\" |20,000,000 ||[[Uyghurs|Uyghur people]]||[[East Turkestan independence movement]]\n|-\n| align=\"center\" |3 ||'''[[File:Flag of the Inner Mongolian People's Party.svg|23px|border]] [[Inner Mongolia]]'''||[[Hohhot]]|| align=\"center\" |1,183,000 || align=\"center\" |25,000,000 ||[[Mongols in China|Chinese Mongols]]||[[Inner Mongolian independence movement]]\n|-\n| align=\"center\" |4 ||'''{{flagdeco|Hong Kong}} [[Hong Kong]]'''||[[Hong Kong]]|| align=\"center\" |1,110 || align=\"center\" |7,500,000 ||[[Hongkongers|Hong Kong people]]||[[Hong Kong independence|Hong Kong independence movement]]\n|-\n| align=\"center\" |5 ||'''{{flagdeco|Macau}} [[Macau]]'''||[[Macau]]|| align=\"center\