r|1,500,000 || [[Ob-Ugric languages|Ob-Ugrians]] ||  Association to Save Yurga\n|}\n\n=== Asian Russia ===\n\n{{flagicon image|Siberian flag.svg}} [[Siberia]] or [[Siberian Federal District]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://region.expert/shaman-prospects/|date=16 December 2019|website=Region Expert|language=ru|url-status=live|accessdate=9 January 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|date=19 January 2020|website=Region Expert|language=ru|url-status=live|accessdate=9 January 2020|url=https://region.expert/poliudova/}}</ref>\n* Ethnic group: {{ill|Sibiryak people|lt=Sibiryak|ru|\u0421\u0438\u0431\u0438\u0440\u044f\u043a\u0438}}\n** Proposed state: {{flagicon image|Siberian flag.svg}} [[Siberian Republic]]\n** Advocacy movements: [[Siberskoye Zemlyachestvo (Autonomy Movement)]], [[Sibir (organization)|Sibir]], [[Free Siberia]], [[Democratic Siberia]] \n** Movement: [[Siberian regionalism]]\n** Political parties: [[Monstration for Siberian Federalization]], [[All-Siberian Democratic Union]], [[Siberian Republican Alliance]], [[Roar of the Taiga (Zov Taugi)]]\n** Organizations: [[Siberian Agreement]], [[Siberian Regional Organization (Siberskoye Zemlyachestvo)]]\n** Militant organization: [[Siberian Liberation Army]]\n\n===Far Eastern Federal District===\n{{flag|Chukotka}}\n* Ethnic group: [[Chukchi people|Chukchis]]\n** Proposed state: [[File:Chukchi independence movement .gif|22px|border]] [[Chukotka Autonomous Okrug|Chukchi Republic]]<ref>{{Cite book | url=https://books.google.com/?id=ZfnWCQAAQBAJ&pg=PA461&dq=Chukotka+stateless+nation#v=onepage&q=Chukotka%20stateless%20nation&f=false |title = Encyclopedia of the Stateless Nations: Ethnic and National Groups Around the World A-Z &#91;4 Volumes&#93;|isbn = 9780313076961|last1 = Minahan|first1 = James|date = 30 May 2002}}</ref>\n*** Advocacy group: [[Chukchi National Revival Movement]]\n*** Political party: [[Chukchi National Republican Party]]\n*** Militant organization: [[Chukot Front]]\n\n{{flag|Koryakia}}\n* Ethnic group: [[Koryaks]]\n** Proposed state: {{flag|Koryakia}}\n*** Advocacy groups: [[Narodovlastie]], [[Chav (Koryakia)|Chav]], [[Tshsanom]] \n*** Movement: [[Koryak Republican Movement]]\n*** Organization: [[Association of the People of North Kamchatka]], [[Association of the People's of the North Association of Indigenous People of Koryak Autonomous Region]]\n\n[[File:Flag of the Far Eastern Republic.svg|22px|border]] [[Far Eastern Republic]] \n* Ethnic groups: [[Russians]], [[Udege people|Udeges]], [[Nanai people|Nanais]] and other various ethnic groups\n** Proposed state:\n*** Socialist: [[File:Flag of the Far Eastern Republic.svg|22px|border]] [[Far Eastern Republic]]\n*** Federalist/Democratic: [[File:Flag of Amur Oblast.svg|22px|border]] [[Far Eastern Republic]]\n** Proposed entity: Far Eastern Republic, including all territories from the Far Eastern Republic and/or modern-day federal subjects associated within the former lands of the aforementioned Far Eastern Republic (Note: This includes the modern-day federal subjects such as: [[Primorsky Krai]], [[Khabarovsk Krai]], [[Jewish Autonomous Oblast]], [[Amur Oblast]], [[Zabaykalsky Krai]] and [[Buryatia]], sometimes federal subjects such as: [[Magadan Oblast]], [[Kamchatka Krai]] and [[Chukotka Autonomous Okrug]] and [[Green Ukraine]] are included based on maximum extent from 1920. It may rarely or sometimes include all federal subjects in [[Far Eastern economic region]] and/or [[Far Eastern Federal District]].)\n**Advocacy movements: [[Far East Forum]], [[Zemyak]], [[Regional Association of the Far East]]\n**Movements: [[Republican Movement (Russia)|Republican Movement]], [[Far East Independence Movement]]\n**Political party: [[Alliance of the Pacific Peoples]]\n**Militant organization: [[Far Eastern People's Front]]\n\n{{flag|Sakha Republic}}\n* Ethnic group: [[Yakuts]]\n** Proposed state: {{flag|Sakha Republic}}\n** Political party: Sakha-Amuk\n\n{{flag|Buryatia}}<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://ukrainian.voanews.com/a/ulan-ude-meeting/1876486.html|title=Buryatia has already started talking about independence from Russia|last=Vorozhko|first=Tatiana|date=21 March 2014|website=Voice of America|language=uk|url-status=live|access-date=31 October 2019}}</ref>\n* Ethnic group: [[Buryats]]\n** Proposed state: {{flag|Buryatia}}\n** Political party:All-Buryat Association for the Development of Culture\n\n[[File:Flag of Momsky rayon (Yakutia).png|22px|border]] [[Severo-Evensky District|Evenia]]\n* Ethnic group: [[Evens]]\n** Proposed State: [[File:Flag of Momsky rayon (Yakutia).png|22px|border]] [[Severo-Evensky District|Evenia]]\n\n{{flag|Jewish Autonomous Oblast|}}\n* Ethnic group: [[Ashkenazi Jews]]\n** Proposed state: {{flag|Jewish Autonomous Oblast}}\n\n[[File:Flag of Nanaysky rayon (Khabarovsk kray).png|22px|border]] [[Nanaisky Raion|Nanaia]]\n* Ethnic group: [[Nanai people|Nanai]] \n** Proposed state: [[File:Flag of Nanaysky rayon (Khabarovsk kray).png|22px]] [[Nanaisky Raion|Nanaia]] \n*** Advocacy group: [[Nanai Cultural Assembly]]\n*** Political party: [[Nanai People's Platform]]\n\n===Siberian Federal District===\n[[File:Flag of Taymyr Autonomous Okrug.svg|22px|border]] [[Taymyrsky Dolgano-Nenetsky District]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://openrussia.org/notes/717067/|title=\"They keep their dead in the barn\": why they cannot bury the dead in Taymyr|last=Korolkova|first=Elizabeth|date=2017-12-07|website=Open Russia|language=ru|url-status=live|access-date=2019-10-02}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.svoboda.org/a/28638658.html|title=Taymyr residents again demand a referendum on autonomy|last=Starinova|first=Julia|date=2017-07-26|website=Radio Liberty|language=ru|url-status=live|access-date=2019-10-02}}</ref>\n* Ethnic groups: [[Dolgans]], [[Nenets people|Nenets]], [[Russians]]\n** Proposed federal subject: {{flag|Taymyr Autonomous Okrug}}\n\n{{flag|Agin-Buryat Autonomous Okrug}} \n* Ethnic group: [[Buryats]]\n** Proposed state: {{flag|Agin-Buryat Autonomous Okrug}} or unification with {{flag|Buryatia}}\n\n{{flag|Altai Republic}}\n* Ethnic group: [[Altai people]]\n** Proposed state: [[File:Flag of the Confederated Republic of Altai.gif|22px|border]] [[Altai Republic|Confederated Republic of Altai]]\n** Movement: Altai-Sayun United Movement\n** Organizations: Altai Turks Associstion, Kurualtai of the Altai People\n** Political parties: Confederal Nation of the Altai Tribes, Ene-Bayat\n\n[[File:Flag of Evenkia.svg|22px|border]] [[Evenk Autonomous Okrug|Evenkia]]\n* Ethnic group: [[Evenks]]\n** Proposed state: [[File:Flag of Evenks.svg|22px|border]] [[Evenkia (country)|Evenkia]]<ref>{{Cite book | url=https://books.google.com/?id=ZfnWCQAAQBAJ&pg=PA587&dq=Evenk+national+movement+stateless+nation#v=onepage&q=Evenk%20national%20movement%20stateless%20nation&f=false | title=Encyclopedia of the Stateless Nations: Ethnic and National Groups Around the World A-Z &#91;4 Volumes&#93;| isbn=9780313076961| last1=Minahan| first1=James| date=30 May 2002}}</ref>\n*** Advocacy group: [[Evenki Homeland]]\n*** Militant organization: [[Evenki National Front]]\n*** Organization: [[Evenki Cultural Council]]\n\n{{flag|Khakassia}}\n* Ethnic group: [[Khakas people|Khakas]] \n** Proposed state: {{flag|Khakassia}}\n*** Advocacy group: [[Khakas Cultural Centre]]\n** Pressure group: [[Chas Khanat]], [[Khaidzhi]]\n** Organization: [[Abakan Tun Association of The Khakas]], [[Congress of The Khakas People]], [[Khakas Council of Elders]]\n\n[[File:Flag of Krasnoselkupsky rayon (Yamal Nenetsia).svg|22px|border]] [[Krasnoselkupsky District|Selkupia]]\n* Ethnic group: [[Selkup people|Selkup]]\n** Proposed state: [[File:Flag of Krasnoselkupsky rayon (Yamal Nenetsia).svg|22px|border]] [[Krasnoselkupsky District|Selkupia]]\n\n[[File:Flag of Tashtagolskiy rayon (Kemerovskaya oblast).gif|22px|border]] [[Gornaya Shoriya|Shor Mountain]]\n* Ethnic group: [[Shors|Shor]]\n** Proposed state: [[File:Flag of the Shor people.png|22px|border]] [[Gornaya Shoriya|Shoria]]\n\n[[File:Flag of Tuva.svg|22px|border]] [[Tuva]]\n* Ethnic group: [[Tuvan people|Tuvans]]\n* Proposed state: [[File:Flag of Tuva.svg|22px|border]] [[Tuva]]\n** Political parties: People's Party of Sovereign Tuva, People's Front \"Free Tuva\", Tiva Turu\n\n[[File:Flag of Ust-Orda Buryat Autonomous Okrug.svg|22px|border]] [[Ust-Orda Buryat Autonomous Okrug]]\n* Ethnic group: [[Buryats]]\n* Proposed state: [[File:Flag of Ust-Orda Buryat Autonomous Okrug.svg|22px|border]] [[Ust-Orda Buryat Autonomous Okrug]] or unification with {{flag|Buryatia}}\n\n===Ural Federal District===\n{{flag|Khanty-Mansi Autonomous Okrug}}<ref>{{Cite book | url=https://books.google.com/?id=up-dDwAAQBAJ&pg=PT27&lpg=PT27&dq=Khanty-Mansi+seperalist#v=onepage&q=Khanty-Mansi%20seperalist&f=false |title = Federalism in China and Russia|isbn = 9781788972192|last1 = Libman|first1 = Alexander|last2 = Rochlitz|first2 = Michael|year = 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book | url=https://books.google.com/?id=VroABgoe4-EC&pg=PA575&lpg=PA575&dq=Khanty-Mansi+seperalist#v=onepage&q=Khanty-Mansi%20seperalist&f=false |title = The Republics and Regions of the Russian Federation: A Guide to Politics, Policies, and Leaders|isbn = 9780765605597|year = 2000}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book | url=https://books.google.com/?id=I_ytDwAAQBAJ&pg=PA58&lpg=PA58&dq=Khanty-Mansi+seperalist#v=onepage&q=Khanty-Mansi%20seperalist&f=false |title = Constructing Grievance: Ethnic Nationalism in Russia's Republics|isbn = 9780801460722|last1 = Giuliano|first1 = Elise|date = 15 March 2011}}</ref>\n* Ethnic group: [[Khanty people]] and [[Mansi people]]\n** Proposed state: {{flag|Khanty-Mansi Autonomous Okrug|Yurga}}\n** Advocacy movements: Association to Save Yurga, Khanty Way, Mansi Way, Ob-Ugrian Union, Society for the Survival and Socio-Economic Development of the Mansi People, Ugrian Association, Youth Public Organization, Yurga Restoration\n\n[[File:Flag of Yamal-Nenets Autonomous District.svg|22px|border]] [[Yamalia]]/[[Nenets Autonomous Okrug]]\n* Ethnic group: [[Nenets people|Nenets]]\n** Proposed state: [[File:Flag of Yamal-Nenets Autonomous District.svg|22px|border]] [[Yamalia|Yamalia/East Nenetsia]]\n** Advocacy group: [[Yamal for Future Generations (Association of the Indigenous People of Yamal-Nenets Autonomus Region)]]\n\n== Saudi Arabia ==\n{{More citations needed section|small=y|date=January 2020}}\n{{Main|Secession in Saudi Arabia}}\n{{See|Ahrar al-Najran|Qatif conflict}}\n\n===Summary===\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"font-size:100%\"\n|-\n!width=75|Number\n!width=275|Land\n!width=125|Capital\n!width=100|Area\n!width=100|Population\n!width=125|Ethnic\n!width=300|Main Political Party\n|-\n| align=center|1 || ''' [[Najran Region|Najran]]''' || '''[[Najran]]''' || align=center|149,511  || align=center|550,000 || [[Arabs|Shia Arab]] || [[Ahrar al-Najran]]\n|-\n| align=center|2 || '''[[File:Flag of Upper Asir.svg|22px|border]] [[Asir]]''' || '''[[Abha]]''' || align=center|76,693 || align=center|2,250,000 || [[Arabs]] || Asser Regional Movement (ARM)\n|-\n| align=center|3 || '''[[File:Flag of the Emirate of Ha'il.svg|22px|border]] [[Ha'il Region|Jabal Shammar]]''' || '''[[Ha'il]]''' || align=center|103,887 || align=center|600,000 || [[Arabs]] || Shammar Revival Movement\n|-\n| align=center|4 || '''[[Eastern Province, Saudi Arabia|Al-Hassa]]''' || '''[[Dammam]]''' || align=center|672,522  || align=center|5,000,000 || [[Arabs|Shia Arab]] || \n|- style=\"background:silver;\"\n| align=\"center\" |'''Total'''||'''{{flagdeco|Saudi Arabia}} [[Saudi Arabia]]'''||'''[[Riyadh]]'''|| align=\"center\" |'''1,002,603'''|| align=\"center\" |'''8,400,000'''||'''[[Saudi Arabia]]'''||'''[[Saudi Arabia]]'''\n|}\n\n[[File:Arabia 1914.png|thumb|200px|The [[Arabian Peninsula]] in 1914.]]\n[[File:Ash_Sharqiyah_in_Saudi_Arabia.svg|thumb|200px|Map of Saudi Arabia with the Eastern Province highlighted.]]\n\nIn 2013 Robin Wright\u2019s colorful map of a politically re-divided Middle East in the New York Times, which illustrated her article \u201cImagining a Remapped Middle East.\u201d The map, entitled \u201cHow 5 Could Become 14,\u201d shows a hypothetical future division of Libya, Iraq, Syria, Yemen, and Saudi Arabia into 14 potential new countries along with two additional city-states. I was immediately reminded of Ralph Peters\u2019 troublesome remapping of the same region. As explained in a previous GeoCurrents post, Peters\u2019 intriguing mental exercise in redrawing national boundaries was widely misinterpreted across the Muslim world as indicating a nefarious plot to enhance US power. As a result, the region\u2019s pronounced anti-Americanism was further inflamed.<ref>http://www.geocurrents.info/geopolitics/myth-nation-state/robin-wrights-audacious-remapping-middle-east</ref><ref>https://moderndiplomacy.eu/2015/03/26/from-one-yemen-to-a-dissolution-of-saudi-arabia/</ref><ref>http://geocurrents.info/wp-content/uploads/2013/10/Robin-Wrights-Remapped-Middle-East.png</ref><ref>http://geocurrents.info/wp-content/uploads/2013/10/Saudi-Arabia-Remapped-by-Robin-Wright.png</ref>\n\nFurthermore, in June 2012 the Yemeni newspaper ''Al-Shareh'' revealed the names of high-ranking Yemeni state officials and tribal sheikhs who had been receiving monthly bribes from Saudi Arabia. This sparked anger among Yemenis, and a group of Yemeni activists founded the \"Asir Movement\" in order to reclaim the provinces of Asir, Najran, and Jizan, which Yemen conceded in the 2000 [[Treaty of Jeddah (2000)|Treaty of Jeddah]]. A \"[[Human rights|rights]] organization which has worked to denounce Saudi Arabia\u2019s abuses in northern Yemen\",<ref name=PressTV>{{cite news|title=Yemen's Houthis standing ground against Saudi Arabia |url= http://www.presstv.com/detail/2014/02/07/349604/houthis-stand-ground-against-s-arabia |work=Press TV| date=February 7, 2014}}</ref> the Asir Movement described itself as a \u201ccivil popular\u201d movement that seeks to raise \"internal Yemeni awareness\" about the situation and to explore legal remedies against Saudi Arabia \"for their involvement and assistance in abdicating Yemen\u2019s historical right to its territories\", all while emphasizing Yemeni unity. The movement sought to speak out against the 2000 Jeddah border agreement as well as the 1934 Taif Agreement that was signed in 1934 to end the [[Saudi\u2013Yemeni War]].<ref>{{cite news|author1=Jomana Farhat|title=Saudi-Yemeni Border: A Line in the Sand|url=http://english.al-akhbar.com/node/8500|work=Al Akhbar|date=June 15, 2012}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Qatif conflict]] refers to the modern phase of [[sectarian]] tensions and violence in Eastern Arabia between Arab Shi'a Muslims and Arab Sunni majority, which has ruled Saudi Arabia since early 20th century. The conflict encompasses civil unrest which has been sporadically ongoing since [[1979 Qatif Uprising|1979 events]], pro-democracy and pro-human rights [[2011\u201312 Saudi Arabian protests|protests]] and occasional armed incidents, which increased in 2017 as part of the [[2017\u201319 Qatif unrest]].\n\n[[Najran Region|Najran]]\n* Ethnic group: [[Arabs|Shia Arab]]\n** Proposed state: [[Najran Region|Najran]]\n** Militant organizations: [[Ismaili Defense Group]], [[Ahrar al-Najran]], [[Najran Valleys Liberation Organization]]\n** Organization: [[Najran Ismaili Association]]\n** Political party: [[Disobedience (political party)|Disobedience (Tamarrod)]], [[Najran Now]]\n\n[[File:Flag of Upper Asir.svg|22px|border]] [[Asir]]\n* Ethnic group: [[Arabs|Arab]]\n** Proposed state: [[File:Flag of Upper Asir.svg|22px|border]] [[Asir]]\n** Advocacy groups: [[Abha Asir Highland Organization]], [[Asser Regional Movement (ARM)]]\n** Movement: [[Asir Movement]], [[Idrisi Movement]]\n** Militant organization: [[Democratic Popular Front for the Liberation of the Pennisula]]\n** Organization: [[European Asir Organization]]\n\n[[File:Flag of the Emirate of Ha'il.svg|22px|border]] [[Emirate of Jabal Shammar|Jabal Shammar]] ([[Ha'il Region]])<ref>https://css.ethz.ch/content/dam/ethz/special-interest/gess/cis/center-for-securities-studies/resources/docs/ISPSW_506_Bodansky.pdf</ref>\n* Ethnic group: [[Arabs|Arab]]\n** Proposed state: [[File:Flag of the Emirate of Ha'il.svg|22px|border]] [[Emirate of Jabal Shammar|Jabal Shammar]]\n** Advocacy groups: [[Dhi Qar Shammar Tribal Union]], [[Jabal Shammar Exile Association]], [[Shamariyeh (organization)|Shamariyeh]]\n** Militant organization: [[Al-Sanadid Forces]]\n** Movements: [[Asir Movement]], [[Idrisi Movement]], [[Shammar Revival Movement]], [[Qajtanite Movement]]\n** Organization: [[Haiyel Shammar People's Organization]]\n** Political party: [[Shammar Nation]]\n\n[[Al-Ahsa Governorate|Al-Hassa]] ([[Eastern Province, Saudi Arabia]]) ([[Qatif conflict]])\n* Ethnic group: [[Arabs|Shia Arab]]\n** Proposed state: [[Al-Ahsa Governorate|Al-Hassa]]\n\n== Sri Lanka ==\n{{Main|Sri Lankan Civil War}}\n\n{{flag|Tamil Eelam}}\n* Ethnic group: [[Sri Lankan Tamil people|Tamil]]\n** Proposed state: [[Tamil Eelam]] or merge with [[Tamil Nadu]], [[India]]\n** Militant organisation: [[Liberation Tigers of Tamil Eelam]] (Active, but militarily dormant since 2009)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.detnews.com/article/20090518/NATION/905180344/1020/Rebels-admit-defeat-in-Sri-Lankan-civil-war|title=Rebels admit defeat in Sri Lankan civil war &#124; detnews.com &#124; The Detroit News|publisher=detnews.com|accessdate=30 May 2009}}{{Dead link|date=June 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.straitstimes.com/asia/se-asia/two-malaysian-dap-assemblymen-eight-others-charged-for-alleged-links-to-terror-group|title=Two Malaysian DAP assemblymen, 8 others charged over alleged links to Liberation Tigers of Tamil Eelam|date=29 October 2019|publisher=The Straits Times}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thestar.com.my/news/nation/2019/10/28/twelve-allegedly-linked-to-ltte-to-be-charged-in-court-tuesday-oct-29|title=Twelve allegedly linked to LTTE to be charged in court|date=28 October 2019|publisher=The Star}}</ref>\n** Political party: [[Tamil National Alliance]]\n** Advocacy groups: [[Transnational Government of Tamil Eelam]]\n** Government in exile: [[Transnational Government of Tamil Eelam]]<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.peacehall.com/news/gb/english/2005/04/200504211050.shtml |title=STATEMENT ON DECLARATION OF SHAN STATE INDEPENDENCE Boxun News |website=peacehall.com |access-date=20 September 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120604194907/http://www.peacehall.com/news/gb/english/2005/04/200504211050.shtml |archive-date=4 June 2012 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=\"tamllib\">{{cite web | url = http://www.sangam.org/2010/12/Tamil_Struggle_18.php | title = Sri Lankan Tamil Struggle \u2013 Chapter 18: The First Sinhalese- Tamil Rift | publisher = Ilankai Tamil Sangam | accessdate =19 January 2012 | work = T. Sabaratnam}}</ref>\n\n== Syria ==\n{{Main|Syrian Civil War}}\n{{Further|Sectarianism and minorities in the Syrian Civil War|Mandate for Syria and the Lebanon|Federalization of Syria}}\n\n[[File:French Mandate for Syria and the Lebanon map en.svg|thumb|Right|Map showing the states of the French Mandate from 1921 to 1922]]\n\n[[File:Ala kurd\u00ean rojava.svg|22px|border]] [[Rojava]]\n* Ethnic and ethno-religious group: [[Kurdish people|Kurdish]], [[Yazidis]]\n** De facto autonomous region: [[File:Ala kurd\u00ean rojava.svg|22px|border]] [[Rojava|Federation of Northern Syria \u2013 Rojava]]\n** Political party: [[Democratic Union Party (Syria)|Democratic Union Party]]\n** Militant organisation: [[People's Defence Units]]\n** Political Movement: [[Democratic Confederalism]], [[Democratic Socialism]], [[Feminism]], [[Ecosocialism]]\n\n;Proposed states:\n\n[[File:Flag of Druze.svg|22px|border]] [[As-Suwayda]]\n* Ethno-religious group: [[Druze]]\n** Proposed state: [[File:Flag of Druze.svg|22px|border]] [[Jabal Druze State|Druze Democratic Republic]]\n** Political parties: [[Progressive Socialist Party (Syria)]]\n** Militant organisations: [[Jaysh al-Muwahhideen]]\n\n[[File:ArameanFlag.png|22px|border]] [[Aram (biblical region)|Aram]] {{citation needed|date=July 2017}} {{original research inline|date=July 2017}}\n* Ethno-religious group: [[Terms for Syriac Christians#Arameans|Arameans]]\n** Proposed state: [[File:ArameanFlag.png|22px|border]] [[Aram (biblical region)|Aramaean Republic]]\n** Political parties: [[Aramean Democratic Organisation]]\n** Advocacy group: [[World Council of Arameans (Syriacs)]]\n\n{{flag|Assyria}}\n* Ethnic group: [[Assyrian people|Assyrian]]\n** Proposed state: {{flag|Assyria|name=Assyrian Democratic Republic}}\n** Political parties: [[Syriac Union Party (Syria)|Syriac Union Party]], [[Assyrian Democratic Organization]]\n** Militant organisations: [[Syriac Military Council]], [[Sutoro]]\n** Advocacy groups: [[Assyria Council of Europe]]\n\n[[File:Official Flag of Syrian Turkmen.jpg|22px|border]] [[Syrian Turkmen]]\n{{See also|Turkish involvement in the Syrian Civil War}}\n* Ethnic group: [[Syrian Turkmen]]\n** Proposed state: [[File:Official Flag of Syrian Turkmen.jpg|22px|border]] Autonomous or free [[Syrian Turkmen|Bay\u0131rbucak]] and [[Aleppo governorate|Northern Aleppo]] (Western Turkmeneli) or [[Turkey]]\n** Political parties: [[Syrian Turkmen Assembly]] (official governing umbrella for [[Syrian Turkmen National Bloc]] and [[Syrian Democratic Turkmen Movement]])\n** Militant organizations: [[Syrian Turkmen Brigades]]\n\n== Taiwan (''de facto'' state) ==\n{{Main|Secession in China|Taiwan independence movement|Retrocession Day}}\n{{See also|Political status of Taiwan|Cross-Strait relations|Foreign relations of Taiwan}}\n'''The {{flagdeco|TWN}} [[Taiwan|Republic of China]] (Taiwan or ROC)''' is a state that has diplomatic relations with 14 [[Member states of the United Nations|United Nations member states]] (as well as the [[Holy See]], an [[United Nations General Assembly observers|observer]]).\n\n*{{flagdeco|TWN}}{{flagdeco|Taiwan Province}} [[Taiwan Province|'''Taiwan Province, Republic of China (Taiwan)''']] \u2014 \"Taiwan Province, Republic of China\" has been officially proclaimed and semi-administered by the [[Republic of China (1912\u20131949)]] since 1945 (Taiwan was annexed by the Republic of China in 1945, [[Retrocession Day|having been recently seized]] from the [[Empire of Japan]]), having existed for around four years prior to the [[Chinese Civil War|establishment of the People's Republic of China]] in mainland China in 1949 and the subsequent exile of the Republic of China from mainland China [[Republic of China retreat to Taiwan|and retreat to Taiwan]] in 1949. However, this administrative division has never had the full power of a \"Taiwan Province\" since its territorial claim, from 1949 and onward, has always overlapped with the seat of the [[Government of the Republic of China|national government of the Republic of China (Taiwan)]] in [[Taipei]]. In the present day, six [[Administrative divisions of Taiwan|province-level subdivisions]] ([[Special municipality (Taiwan)|special municipalities]]) have been [[Secession|carved out of]] (seceded from) Taiwan Province (by the Taiwanese (ROC) government), and, therefore, Taiwan Province is ''de jure'' (under [[Law of Taiwan|Taiwanese (ROC) law]]) divided into seven distinct province-level subdivisions, including itself. These province-level subdivisions are {{flagdeco|Kaohsiung}} [[Kaohsiung]], {{flagdeco|New Taipei}} [[New Taipei City|New Taipei]], {{flagdeco|Taichung}} [[Taichung]], {{flagdeco|Tainan}} [[Tainan]], {{flagdeco|Taipei}} [[Taipei]], {{flagdeco|Taiwan Province}}{{flagdeco|Penghu County}} [[Taiwan Province|Taiwan]] (including [[Penghu]]), and {{flagdeco|Taoyuan}} [[Taoyuan, Taiwan|Taoyuan]], and they are accompanied by another province-level subdivision (nominally part of mainland China), {{flagdeco|Republic of China}}{{flagdeco|Kinmen}}{{flagdeco|Lienchiang County}} [[Fujian Province, Republic of China|Fujian (Fukien)]] (including [[Kinmen]] and [[Matsu Islands|Matsu]]).\n\n=== Indigenous Taiwanese autonomy movement ===\n{{See also|Taiwanese indigenous peoples|History of Taiwan|Prehistory of Taiwan}}\n\n* Ethnic group: [[Taiwanese indigenous peoples]] ([[Amis people|Amis]], [[Paiwan people|Paiwan]] etc.)\n**Proposed autonomous region: Indigenous Taiwanese communities in Eastern Taiwan\n***Movement: Indigenous Taiwanese autonomy movement\n***Political parties: [[Taiwan First Nations Party]]\n*** Advocacy groups: [[Council of Indigenous Peoples]]\n**Proposed autonomous region: Indigenous Taiwanese communities in Western Taiwan and Eastern Taiwan\n***Movement: Recognition of Indigenous Taiwanese plains peoples, Indigenous Taiwanese autonomy movement\n***Political parties: [[Taiwan First Nations Party]]\n***Advocacy groups: [[Council of Indigenous Peoples]]\n\n=== Taiwan independence movement ===\n{{Main|Taiwan independence movement}}\n{{See also|History of Taiwan|Taiwanese nationalism|Taiwanese identity}}{{flagdeco|TWN}} '''[[Taiwan|Republic of China (Taiwan)]] ('''{{flagdeco|Kaohsiung}} '''[[Kaohsiung]],''' {{flagdeco|New Taipei}} '''[[New Taipei City|New Taipei]],''' {{flagdeco|Taichung}} '''[[Taichung]],''' {{flagdeco|Tainan}} '''[[Tainan]],''' {{flagdeco|Taipei}} '''[[Taipei]],''' {{flagdeco|Taiwan Province}}{{flagdeco|Penghu County}} '''[[Taiwan Province|Taiwan]]-[[Penghu]],''' {{flagdeco|Taoyuan}} '''[[Taoyuan, Taiwan|Taoyuan]])'''\n{{See also|Administrative divisions of Taiwan|Geography of Taiwan|List of islands of Taiwan}}\n\n* Ethnic group: [[Taiwanese people]] ([[Hakka people#Taiwan|Hakka Taiwanese]], [[Hoklo Taiwanese]], [[Kinmen|Kinmenese people]], [[Taiwanese indigenous peoples]], [[Mainland Chinese#Mainlanders in Taiwan|Taiwanese Waishengren]])\n**Proposed state:  {{flagdeco|TWN}}[[File:Flag of World Taiwanese Congress.svg|22px|border]] [[Taiwan independence movement|Republic of Taiwan]]\n***Movement: [[Taiwan independence movement]], [[Taiwanese nationalism]]\n****Note: The [[Democratic Progressive Party]] (DPP) has been democratically elected to power in the Republic of China (Taiwan) four times; in [[2000 Taiwanese presidential election|2000 (until 2004)]], in [[2004 Taiwanese presidential election|2004 (until 2008)]], in [[2016 Taiwanese presidential election|2016 (until 2020)]], and in [[2020 Taiwanese presidential election|2020 (until 2024)]]. Although the DPP has been the nominal ruling party of the Republic of China throughout these four ruling terms, the DPP has been pushing a pro-Taiwan independence agenda, whether tacitly or overtly. Some representatives of the DPP, such as [[William Lai]], argue that Taiwan independence should not even be considered an \"independence movement\" but is rather the recognition of the reality of the current situation of the [[Republic of China on Taiwan]]. Many supporters of Taiwan independence believe that Taiwan, under the formal name of the \"Republic of China\", is already an independent country from China, under the formal name of the \"People's Republic of China\".\n***Political parties: [[Pan-Green Coalition]] ([[Democratic Progressive Party]], [[Taiwan Solidarity Union]], [[Taiwan Independence Party]]), [[New Power Party]], [[Taiwan Statebuilding Party]]\n***Advocacy groups: Keep Taiwan Free (Taiwanese organisation), [[World United Formosans for Independence]]\n***Claimed territories: Taiwan (Kaohsiung, New Taipei, Taichung, Tainan, Taipei, Taiwan-Penghu, Taoyuan)\n***Area of claimed territories: Roughly 36,000&nbsp;km<sup>2</sup>\n***Population of claimed territories: Roughly 24,000,000 people\n{{flagdeco|Kinmen}}{{flagdeco|TWN}} '''[[Kinmen|Kinmen County, Republic of China (Taiwan)]] (Kinmen)''' \u2014 Independence movement{{See also|Kinmen|Taiwan independence movement#The issue of Kinmen (Quemoy) and Matsu (Lienchiang)}}\n\n* Ethnic group: Kinmenese people, [[Taiwanese people]]\n**Proposed unification with a proposed state: {{flagdeco|Kinmen}}{{flagdeco|TWN}}[[File:Flag of World Taiwanese Congress.svg|22px|border]] Kinmen County, Republic of Taiwan\n***Movement: Kinmen-Taiwan unification movement, [[Taiwan independence movement]], [[Taiwanese nationalism]]\n****Note: [[Kinmen]] is currently ruled by the [[Taiwan|Republic of China (Taiwan)]], so it and Taiwan are ''de facto'' already united. However, Kinmen's history is highly distinct from Taiwan's, and they've only really had a shared history since 1949, when the [[Republic of China retreat to Taiwan|Republic of China retreated to Taiwan]]. Furthermore, Kinmen's recent history has been largely shaped by military conflict between the ROC and the PRC and by the fact that [[Martial law in Taiwan|martial law]] was abolished in Kinmen in 1992, five years after it was abolished in Taiwan (in 1987). If the \"[[Taiwan independence movement|Republic of Taiwan]]\" were to be established, many people are uncertain of whether Kinmen should be included in this new country. Some young people in Kinmen identify as Taiwanese but the Kinmen County government is pushing a [[Chinese unification|pro-(re)unification]] (with the PRC) agenda.\n***Area of Kinmen: Roughly 150&nbsp;km<sup>2</sup>\n***Population of Kinmen: Roughly 130,000 people\n\n=== Various Chinese (re)unification movements ===\n{{Main|Chinese unification|Greater China|Chinese Civil War}}\n{{See also|Two Chinas|1992 Consensus|Anti-Secession Law}}{{flagdeco|TWN}} '''[[Taiwan|Republic of China (Taiwan)]] ({{flagdeco|Kaohsiung}} KH, {{flagdeco|Kinmen}} Kinmen, {{flagdeco|Lienchiang County}} Matsu, {{flagdeco|New Taipei}} NT, {{flagdeco|Taichung}} TC, {{flagdeco|Tainan}} TN, {{flagdeco|Taipei}} TP, {{flagdeco|Taiwan Province}}TW-{{flagdeco|Penghu County}}PH, {{flagdeco|Taoyuan}}TY)''' \u2014 Irredentist movement\n{{See also|One-China policy|Taiwan Province, People's Republic of China|Taiwan, China}}\n\n* Ethnic group: [[Chinese people]], [[Taiwanese people]]\n**Proposed unification with a foreign state: {{flagdeco|CHN}}{{flagdeco|HKG}}{{flagdeco|MAC}}{{flagdeco|TWN}} [[Greater China]] ([[China]])\n***Movement: [[Chinese unification|Chinese (re)unification movement]], [[Chinese nationalism]]\n**** Note: This movement, [[Irredentism|irredentist]] in nature, is strongly pushed by the [[Government of China|Chinese (PRC) government]] and forms a [[One-China policy|core component]] of the country's [[Politics of China|national]] and [[Foreign relations of China|foreign policy]]. Around 2% of Taiwanese (ROC) society supports this movement.\n***Claimed territories: China (mainland), Hong Kong, Macau, Taiwan\n*** Area of claimed territories: Roughly 9,630,000&nbsp;km<sup>2</sup>\n*** Population of claimed territories: Roughly 1,460,000,000 people\n\n'''{{flagdeco|Kinmen}}{{flagdeco|TWN}} [[Kinmen|Kinmen County, Republic of China (Taiwan)]] (Kinmen)''' \u2014 Irredentist movement\n\n{{See also|Kinmen|Special economic zones of China|Chinese unification}}\n\n* Ethnic group: Chinese people, [[Kinmen|Kinmenese people]]\n**Proposed unification with a foreign state alongside semi-autonomy: {{flagdeco|PRC}}{{flagdeco|Kinmen}}{{flagdeco|TWN}} Kinmen [[Special economic zones of China|Special Economic Zone]] of the People's Republic of China\n***Movement: Kinmen-China (re)unification movement, [[Chinese unification|Chinese (re)unification movement]], [[Chinese nationalism]]\n****Note: This movement, [[Irredentism|irredentist]] in nature, is strongly pushed by the [[Government of China|Chinese (PRC) government]]. Kinmen is viewed by the Chinese (PRC) government as a place where Chinese (re)unification experiments can be conducted, in preparation for the ultimate goal of annexing the [[Geography of Taiwan|island of Taiwan]]. The Kinmen County government has frequently clashed with the [[Mainland Affairs Council|Taiwan Mainland Affairs Council]] (which oversees relations with the PRC) over its willingness to allow the Chinese (PRC) government to infiltrate its society, economy, politics, cultural institutions, religious institutions, educational institutions, and local communities. It is unknown what percentage of Kinmenese society supports this movement but it is known that the Kinmen County government supports this movement and that it has been actively pushing for Kinmen's annexation into China (PRC).\n*** Area of Kinmen: Roughly 150&nbsp;km<sup>2</sup>\n***Population of Kinmen: Roughly 130,000 people\n\n'''Chinese (re)unification under the ROC'''\n\n{{See also|Three Principles of the People|Project National Glory|Communist bandit}}\n\nThis is a variant of the Chinese (re)unification movement that advocates for the ROC to become the ruling regime of China again, replacing the PRC. Most members and supporters of the [[Pan-Blue Coalition]] in Taiwan, led by the [[Kuomintang|Chinese Nationalist Party (Kuomintang)]], support this movement, whether vaguely or strongly.\n\n* Note: Some proponents of this movement also advocate for the annexation (into China) of {{flagdeco|MNG}} [[Mongolia]] and other regions that were previously administered by the [[Qing dynasty]] (1644\u20131911), the Qing dynasty having been a [[History of China|historical regime of China]] preceding both the PRC and the ROC.\n\n'''Chinese (re)unification under a hypothetical \"New China\"'''\n\n{{See also|Chinese democracy movement|Chinese economic reform|Neoauthoritarianism (China)}}\n\nThis is another variant of the Chinese (re)unification movement. It advocates for the (re)unification of China (PRC) and Taiwan (ROC) under a hypothetical \"New China\". Proponents of this movement believe that both the PRC and the ROC have expired and that the only logical solution that is fair to both parties is to overthrow both regimes and replace them with a single \"New China\" regime that possesses characteristics of both the PRC and the ROC, as well as its own unique traits. Visions for such a \"New China\" range from a \"[[dictatorship]]\" to a \"[[democracy]]\". Vague support for this movement is widespread, but strong support for this movement is rare.\n\n== Tajikistan ==\n{{Main|Secession in Tajikistan}}\n\n[[Gorno-Badakhshan Autonomous Region|Badakhshan]]\n* Ethnic group: [[Pamiri people|Pamiri]]\n** Proposed state: [[United Badakhshan Peoples Republic]]<ref name=Badakhshon>{{cite web |url=http://www.geocities.com/Paris/9305/sheproot.html |title=Roots of the Conflict |publisher=El Gringo |accessdate=10 April 2009 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20091023215821/http://geocities.com/Paris/9305/sheproot.html |archivedate=23 October 2009}}</ref>\n** Political party: [[Lali Badakhshon]]<ref name=Badakhshon />\n\n== Thailand ==\n{{Main|South Thailand insurgency}}\n\n[[File:Pattani Flag.png|22px|border]] [[Patani (region)|Patani]]\n* Ethnic group: [[Thai Malays|Pattani Malays]]\n** Proposed state: [[File:Flag of Pattani.svg|22px|border]] [[Pattani Sultanate|Pattani Darul Makrif]],<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.globalsecurity.org/military/world/para/pulo.htm |title=Pattani United Liberation Organization (PULO) |publisher=GlobalSecurity.org |accessdate=10 April 2009 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090310155947/http://www.globalsecurity.org/military/world/para/pulo.htm |archive-date=10 March 2009 |url-status=live }}</ref>  unification with {{flag|Malaysia}}<ref>{{cite web|url=https://bm.cari.com.my/forum.php?mod=viewthread&tid=673099|title=Bendera Malaysia dinaikkan di selatan Thai|date=1 September 2012|website=cari.com.my|language=Malay}}</ref>\n** Militant organisation: [[Patani United Liberation Organisation]], [[Barisan Revolusi Nasional|Patani Malays National Revolutionary Front]], [[Runda Kumpulan Kecil]], [[Gerakan Mujahidin Islam Patani|Pattani Islamic Mujahideen Movement]], [[Islamic Liberation Front of Patani]]\n\n== Turkey ==\n{{See also|Minorities in Turkey}}\n{{Further|Human rights of Kurdish people in Turkey|Turkish nationalism|Turkish War of Independence|Greek genocide|Republic of Hatay|Western Armenia|Treaty of S\u00e8vres|Treaty of Lausanne}}\n\n[[File:Ethnolinguistic map of Turkey.jpg|thumb|right|300px|Ethnic Groups of Turkey.]]\n[[File:Kurdish majority Turkey-es.svg|thumb|right|300px|Map showing Kurdish majority areas within Turkey.]]\n\n[[File:Flag of Kurdistan.svg|22px|border]] [[Northern Kurdistan]]<ref>{{cite web |url=https://fas.org/irp/world/para/pkk.htm |title=Kurdistan Workers' Party (PKK) |work=[[Federation of American Scientists]] |accessdate=23 July 2008 |date=21 May 2004 |first=John |last=Pike |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080428065853/http://www.fas.org/irp/world/para/pkk.htm |archive-date=28 April 2008 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n{{Main|Kurdish nationalism|United Kurdistan|Kurdish Question|Kurdish Genocide}}\n* Ethnic group: [[Kurdish people|Kurdish]]\n** Proposed state: [[File:Flag of Kurdistan.svg|22px|border]] [[Kurdistan]]\n** Militant organisations: [[Kurdistan Workers Party]] (PKK), [[Group of Communities in Kurdistan]] (KCK), [[Kurdistan Freedom Hawks]] (TAK), [[Democrat Party of Kurdistan/North]] (PDK/Bakur), [[Revolutionary Party of Kurdistan]] (P\u015eK), [[Communist Party of Kurdistan]] (KKP)\n\n{{flag|Assyria}} {{Main|Assyrian nationalism|Assyrian struggle for independence|Assyrian genocide}}\n* Ethnic group: [[Assyrian people|Assyrian]]\n** Proposed state: {{flag|Assyria|name=Assyrian Democratic Republic}}\n** Political parties: [[Assyrian Democratic Movement]], [[Assyria Liberation Party]]\n** Militant organisations: [[Nineveh Plain Protection Units]], [[Dwekh Nawsha]]\n** Advocacy groups: [[Assyrian General Conference]], [[Assyria Council of Europe]]\n\n== Uzbekistan ==\n{{Main|Secession in Uzbekistan}}\n\n[[File:Flag of Karakalpakstan.svg|22px|border]] [[Karakalpakstan]]\n* Ethnic group: [[Karakalpaks]]\n** Proposed state: [[File:Flag of Karakalpakstan.svg|22px|border]] [[Republic of Karakalpakstan]]\n** Advocacy group: [[Free Karakalpakstan National Revival Party]]<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.rferl.org/content/article/1079744.html |title=Uzbekistan: Shadowy Group Agitates For 'Free Karakalpakstan' |publisher=Radio Free Europe/Radio Liberty |date=5 April 2008 |accessdate=11 April 2009 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090217020232/http://www.rferl.org/content/Article/1079744.html |archive-date=17 February 2009 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n== Vietnam ==\n{{Main|Secession in Vietnam}}\n\n[[File:Flag of KKF.svg|20px|]] [[Khmers Kampuchea-Krom Federation]]\n\n* Ethnic group: [[Khmer people]]\n\n[[Montagnard Foundation, Inc.]]\n* Ethnic group: [[Indigenous peoples of the Central Highlands in Vietnam]]\n\n== Yemen ==\n{{Main|Secession in Yemen}}\n{{See|Southern Movement|Greater Yemen}}\n\n[[File:Divided Yemen.svg|thumb|Yemen prior to unification|300px]]\n\n*[[File:Flag of South Yemen.svg|22px|border]] [[South Yemen]]\n** Proposed state: [[File:Flag of South Yemen.svg|22px|border]] [[South Arabia]],<ref>{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/world/middle_east/8378727.stm |title=Five killed at secessionist protest in south Yemen |publisher=BBC |accessdate=25 November 2009 |date=25 November 2009 |location=London}}</ref>  {{flagicon image|Flag of the State of Aden.svg}} [[State of Aden]]\n** De facto state: [[Southern Transitional Council]]<ref name=\"alaraby\">{{cite web |url=https://www.alaraby.co.uk/english/news/2017/5/16/gcc-aden-based-southern-transitional-council-doomed-to-fail |author=The New Arab |publisher=alaraby.co.uk |title=GCC: Aden-based Southern Transitional Council 'doomed to fail' |accessdate=8 June 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170729134839/https://www.alaraby.co.uk/english/news/2017/5/16/gcc-aden-based-southern-transitional-council-doomed-to-fail |archive-date=29 July 2017 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=\"alaraby2\">{{cite web |url=https://www.alaraby.co.uk/english/News/2017/5/11/Governor-turned-president-Adens-Al-Zubaidi-announces-council-to-govern-South-Yemen |author=The New Arab |publisher=alaraby.co.uk |title=Banished Aden governor forms independent 'South Yemen' council |accessdate=8 June 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170511222357/https://www.alaraby.co.uk/english/news/2017/5/11/governor-turned-president-adens-al-zubaidi-announces-council-to-govern-south-yemen |archive-date=11 May 2017 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=\"aawsat\">{{cite web |url=https://english.aawsat.com/theaawsat/news-middle-east/thirty-southern-figures-reject-transitional-council-aden |author=Saudi Research & Marketing (uk) Ltd |work=Asharq Al-Awsat |title=Thirty Southern Figures Reject Transitional Council in Aden \u2013 ASHARQ AL-AWSAT English |accessdate=8 June 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170517064844/http://english.aawsat.com/theaawsat/news-middle-east/thirty-southern-figures-reject-transitional-council-aden |archive-date=17 May 2017 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n*** Political party: [[South Yemen Movement]]\n*[[File:Flag of Hadhramaut.svg|22px|border]] [[Hadhramaut]]\n* Ethnic group: [[Arabs|Arab]]\n** Proposed state: [[File:Kathiri flag.svg|22px|border]] [[Kathiri]], [[File:Flag of Quaiti Hadramaut.svg|22px|border]] [[Qu'aiti]], {{flagicon image|Flag of Wahidi Balhaf.svg}} [[Wahidi Balhaf]], {{flagicon image|Mahraflag.svg}} [[Mahra Sultanate|Mahra]]<ref name=\"geocurrents.info\">{{cite web |url=http://www.geocurrents.info/geopolitics/autonomous-zones/yemens-beleaguered-al-mahrah-seeks-autonomy |title=Yemen's Beleaguered Al Mahrah Seeks Autonomy |access-date=14 July 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150714234058/http://www.geocurrents.info/geopolitics/autonomous-zones/yemens-beleaguered-al-mahrah-seeks-autonomy |archive-date=14 July 2015 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.merip.org/mer/mer263/revolution-socotra |title=Revolution in Socotra \u2013 Middle East Research and Information Project |website=merip.org |access-date=12 February 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150212180956/http://www.merip.org/mer/mer263/revolution-socotra |archive-date=12 February 2015 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.yementimes.com/en/1716/intreview/2950/%E2%80%9CIt%